[{'created': '2018-06-01 17:50:20.000000000', 'message': 'Move database creation into role (nova)

There is no record for why we implement the database creation outside
of the role in the playbook, when we could do it inside the role.

Implementing it inside the role allows us to reduce the quantity of
group_vars duplicated from the role, and allows us to better document
the required variables in the role. The delegation can still be done
as it is done in the playbook too.

In this patch we remove the test-vars which were duplicated from the
role, and remove the DB setup tasks as they are no longer required.

Change-Id: Ie74023c542858f1017509689a3dc3b402614f3d4
Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/571785
'}]
commit_message:
Move database creation into role (nova)

There is no record for why we implement the database creation outside
of the role in the playbook, when we could do it inside the role.

Implementing it inside the role allows us to reduce the quantity of
group_vars duplicated from the role, and allows us to better document
the required variables in the role. The delegation can still be done
as it is done in the playbook too.

In this patch we remove the test-vars which were duplicated from the
role, and remove the DB setup tasks as they are no longer required.

Change-Id: Ie74023c542858f1017509689a3dc3b402614f3d4
Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/571785

commit_message:
Update to use oslo.messaging services for RPC and Notify

This introduces oslo.messaging variables that define the RPC and Notify
transports for the OpenStack services. These parameters replace the
rabbitmq values and are used to generate the messaging transport_url for
the service. The association of the messaging backend server to the
oslo.messaging service will be transparent to the designate service.

This patch:
* Add oslo.messaging variables for RPC and Notify to defaults
* Update transport_url generation (add for notification)
* Add oslo.messaging to tests inventory
* Update tests
* Add releaes note
* Update README and example playbook

Change-Id: I620a13e1ea3c24c8bd31c02206613d37d769dd30

commit_message:
Updated RBac test cases for update/delete volume image metadata

Add logic to check for 'volume_image_metadata' attribute in the response as the
server will still respond with 200 if the user does not have the permission to
perform the action. The difference will be the present or not present of the
'volume_image_metadata' attribute.

Change-Id: I489a89c67e39108f4f5ceb86283b4c9a30b58ff5

commit_message:
Add upgrade jobs for CentOS 7

This adds an upgrade job for CentOS 7, we purposely do not add a
non-voting one because we can simply add voting: false in the
project stanza which is the recommended way of doing things as
per infra.

Change-Id: I804ecab571f8e70fc01d86741246dd8cbafb15fb

commit_message:
Don't skip DVR port while neutron-openvswitch-agent is restared.

neutron-openvswitch-agent will refresh flows when it's restarted.
But the port's binding status is not changed, update_port_postcommit
will be skipped at function '_update_individual_port_db_status' in
'neutron/plugins/ml2/plugin.py', l2pop don't handle DVR ports, the
fdb entries about DVR port will not be added.

So, we can't skip DVR port at notify_l2pop_port_wiring when agent
is restared.

Closes-Bug: #1773286
Change-Id: I54e3db4822830a0c83daf7b5150575f8d6e2497b

commit_message:
Specify placeholder testenv command for tox>=2.5

After tox 2.5.0 usage on OpenStack infrastructure for build jobs,
current tox.ini fails with the following error message:

"ERROR: Commands not specified. Please update relevant section of
.../tox.ini".

This commit proposes a placeholder commands line in [testenv]
not to occur the build job failure for tox>=2.5.

Change-Id: I004dbef8da369c5d6dc8f90880738636b8ec5cfd

   traits in a "tree", one of whose "branch" has requested traits.
   This is reported in bug#1771707.
2) Not all the resource providers in a tree are returned
   in provider_summaries. This is done later under the
   blueprint: placement-return-all-resources.
3) It doesn't support cases where there are sharing providers in the
   system.

These are well described in test cases and will be addressed in
following patches.

Blueprint: nested-resource-providers-allocation-candidates
Change-Id: Ib119a7e14d83a3562519b4653fb0813f2d31af21
Related-Bug: #1771707

commit_message:
Return nested providers in get_by_request

This patch start to return nested providers in get_by_requests().
However, this is not complete because

1) It leaves a bug that placement returns a "branch" without requested
   traits in a "tree", one of whose "branch" has requested traits.
   This is reported in bug#1771707.
2) Not all the resource providers in a tree are returned
   in provider_summaries. This is done later under the
   blueprint: placement-return-all-resources.
3) It doesn't support cases where there are sharing providers in the
   system.

These are well described in test cases and will be addressed in
following patches.

Blueprint: nested-resource-providers-allocation-candidates
Change-Id: Ib119a7e14d83a3562519b4653fb0813f2d31af21
Related-Bug: #1771707

commit_message:
ffu: Introduce Nova fast-forward upgrade tasks

fast_forward_upgrade_tasks for Nova covering Ocata and Pike.
- Service status check
- Stop services when updating from Ocata to Pike
- Update nova packages
- Db sync

commit_message:
Show Heat events by default

Commit I105fb6b37769411178cff5f2c8ea0496f2a9cd2e changed the default
behavior such that Heat events aren't shown by default during a
deployment. This is a regression in usability. This patch restores the
previous behavior such that the Heat stack events are shown even when
--verbose is not passed.

Change-Id: If36c362aaef069da5a41ce74aede9aa2ba993463

commit_message:
db: Add network_requests to instance_extra

Add a deferred-load column to the instance_extras table, which can be
used to store a serialized representation of the 'NetworkRequestList'
object for use later.

The object-related parts of this are included in a separate patch.

Part of blueprint numa-aware-vswitches

Change-Id: I1105a5c4e8f1e6974006943a6d2a379f31d57d6d

commit_message:
Add --overcloud-ssh-network

In some cases, we may not want to always assume the ctlplane as the
network to use for both ssh access to the overcloud nodes, and for
generating the ansible inventory. This patches adds a new cli argument,
--overcloud-ssh-network that can be used to set the network name to be
used. Defaults to ctlplane.

Depends-On: I1e3f9a5142bff5e4f77e5e40df164089d9144652
Change-Id: I767984623c7d2402b10bae3d30b695783166f6bf

commit_message:
Create config-download-latest symlink

Each time the config-download workflow is run, create a symlink at
/var/lib/mistral/config-download-latest that will point to the latest
execution uuid under /var/lib/mistral. This will make it easier for
users to quickly find the latest config-download working directory.

Change-Id: I9375f343a70653203cb984065e14fe616a35c5cc

[{'created': '2018-06-06 01:12:55.000000000', 'message': "Ensure resource class cache when listing usages

In rare circumstances it is possible to list usages in a new placement
process that has not yet instantiated the _RC_CACHE but for which
there are inventories and allocations in the database (added by
other processes running against the same db). Before this change
that would cause a 500 error (AttributeError) when the Usage objects
in the UsageList were instantiated.

The fix is to added _ensure_rc_cache to the two list methods. The
addition is done there rather than in the _from_db_object as the
latter would cause a lot of redundant checks.

welcome.

commit_message:
Ensure resource class cache when listing usages

In rare circumstances it is possible to list usages in a new placement
process that has not yet instantiated the _RC_CACHE but for which
there are inventories and allocations in the database (added by
other processes running against the same db). Before this change
that would cause a 500 error (AttributeError) when the Usage objects
in the UsageList were instantiated.

The fix is to added _ensure_rc_cache to the two list methods. The
addition is done there rather than in the _from_db_object as the
latter would cause a lot of redundant checks.

While we could probably devise a test for this, it's perhaps good
enough to evaluate the change by inspection. If not, suggestions
welcome.

Change-Id: I00f7dee26f031366dbc0d3d6a03abe89afeb85fd
Closes-Bug: #1775308

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I02ef155ef47a5eaddf9de902ad3608bee677fbcf
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Move database creation into role (neutron)

There is no record for why we implement the database creation outside
of the role in the playbook, when we could do it inside the role.

Implementing it inside the role allows us to reduce the quantity of
group_vars duplicated from the role, and allows us to better document
the required variables in the role. The delegation can still be done
as it is done in the playbook too.

In this patch we remove the group_vars which were duplicated from the
role, and remove the DB setup tasks as they are no longer required.

Change-Id: I95971cc58aedfaf88cc209e81aa1848b9e6990f6
Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/571781

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I922ca42cb37a72be1bfe0765c17b075d6e08e1fa
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Move database creation into role

There is no record for why we implement the database creation outside
of the role in the playbook, when we could do it inside the role.

Implementing it inside the role allows us to reduce the quantity of
group_vars duplicated from the role, and allows us to better document
the required variables in the role. The delegation can still be done
as it is done in the playbook too.

In this patch we implement a new variable called 'nova_db_setup_host'
which is used in the role to allow delegation of the database setup
task to any host, but defaults to the first member of the galera_all
host group. We also document the variable nova_galera_address which
has been used for a long time, but never documented.

Change-Id: I7f977b2c24dcd20a4a7e8d32c13fb6c66127ce9c

Filtering of port OVO based on ids of security groups which
are used by ports is now available.

commit_message:
Add system boot mode support

This change adds the ability to read and (for some
drivers) change system boot mode via Redfish call.

At present just Legacy and Uefi boot modes are supported.

Story: 1741062
Task: 12045

commit_message:
Mark stacks returned by get loaded

When calling stacks.get, mark the returning stacks as loaded, so that
attribute retrieval works right away. If not, any getattr on the Stack
will call get() which will request the stack again (and ignore things
like resolve_outputs).

Change-Id: I3a3f25aa0c6f88e7e4274107c0578fd30dc9f155
Related-Bug: #1774958

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I1c8016a76062f21c7413da9fc3d422677a40712e
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

When logging with color, it is necessary to reset the color at the
end of each line to avoid the color bleeding into subsequent log
lines.  This change adds a new key to the record called 'reset_color'

commit_message:
Provide reset_color key on log record

When logging with color, it is necessary to reset the color at the
end of each line to avoid the color bleeding into subsequent log
lines.  This change adds a new key to the record called 'reset_color'
that serves as a shortcut to the escape sequence to reset the color.
It also provides documentation for the ColorHandler class that
explains how to use it.

Change-Id: I68f1c716cbed241f79fa65dae1affe810b8e6e30
Closes-Bug: 1731477

commit_message:
dev mode: Add support for sahara

Provide support fot kolla dev mode in sahara. When
'kolla_dev_mode' or 'sahara_dev_mode' variables are
enabled, source code of sahara  project will be  cloned
and  mounted automatically

Partially implements: blueprint mount-sources

Errors running `python setup.py check -r -s` due to required

not 'author-email'.

commit_message:
Fix package check errors

Errors running `python setup.py check -r -s` due to required
metadata for the package caused by having 'author' set but
not 'author-email'.

Full error is:

```
python setup.py check -r -s
running check
warning: check: missing meta-data: if 'author' supplied, 'author_email' must be
supplied too

error: The docutils package is needed.
```

This updates both author and author-email to be consistent
with the values used in other OpenStack projects.

Change-Id: Icdcb9b9328e361ba4883af5b464c9968f72607e8

commit_message:
Relax the strict PyYAML dependency

Fuel plugin builder demands PyYAML 3.10 stricly, since we have the 3.11
version in packages it doesn't satisfy pip when FPB is being installed.
It turns out that in may cases pip downgrades PyYAML to 3.10 on-the-fly,
this causes side-effects if some modules of 3.11 were loaded during the
downgrade.

Change-Id: Ifbd5b0ed70a6522a1417077beeec2cc7e226b215
Closes-Bug: #1674385

commit_message:
Spec for volume multiattach enhancements

This spec proposes adding a compute API microversion to allow
creating multiple servers in the same request using the same
multiattach volume and to allow the user to specify the attach
mode when attaching volumes to a server.

APIImpact

Spec for blueprint volume-multiattach-enhancements

Change-Id: If75f0b0a19411b553e04643c37921ef4958933f2

- either we consider a config option is not viable because there are alternatives like a management CLI - but I don't think we have a good one as of now
- or, the config option is the only way, but still subject to improvements (like for usage by CMS), and I'm up to other ideas. I surely understand that writing a JSONified dict is errorprone."}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2018-03-30 13:25:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Okay, the discussion following Dan's review has pushed me over the edge.  Here's what I've concluded (could still be wrong):

- Even in Generic Device Management-land, the file describing device types, addresses, etc. is going to need to be *virt driver-specific*.  That being the case, you might as well do it now, because you'll be free to change the format in lockstep with its driver going forward.  Yes, you have to maintain backward compatibility with config files in existing deployments, but that's no different a problem than you're introducing by using config.
- JSON/python dict via oslo_config sucks.  Use YAML."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2018-04-16 14:39:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(7 comments)'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2018-04-23 15:36:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2018-05-14 17:07:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2018-05-14 18:50:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)

I suppose this is fine.

Obviously, I'd prefer to have a YAML-based way of providing inventory and host device information, but we're not going to go that route.

The thing I do *not* want to see is the vendor-specific vGPU types/names leaking out into the user-facing interface via a trait or (worse) a custom resource class on flavors.

Sylvain, what is the plan with regards to how flavors will convey the actual traits that comprise the various vGPU types?

For example, a user will want to specify that they want one VGPU resource class with the following standard traits:

 * HW_GPU_RESOLUTION_W3840H2160
 * HW_GPU_MAX_DISPLAY_HEADS_2
 * HW_GPU_API_DXVA
 * HW_GPU_API_OPENGL_V4_5

There are a number of Nvidia vGPU types that would meet the above requirements: M60-8Q, M60-4Q, M6-8Q, M6-4Q.

How are you planning to expose the actual capabilities (the traits) instead of vendor product IDs?

-jay"}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2018-05-14 19:37:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

>Sylvain, what is the plan with regards to how flavors will convey the >actual traits that comprise the various vGPU types?
>
>For example, a user will want to specify that they want one VGPU resource class with the following standard traits:
>
>How are you planning to expose the actual capabilities (the traits) >instead of vendor product IDs?

Thanks for that good question. I was thinking of providing the same behaviour of PCI aliases for the GPU types too, like we already have for PCI passthrough.

For example :
[pci]
alias = { "vendor_id":"8086", "product_id":"154d", "device_type":"type-PF", "name":"a1" }

Then the libvirt driver would pass a custom trait like CUSTOM_GPU_A1

That said, I don't think it's related to this spec, maybe discussing on a separate spec ?'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2018-05-15 14:21:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> Obviously, I'd prefer to have a YAML-based way of providing
 > inventory and host device information, but we're not going to go
 > that route.
 > 
 > The thing I do *not* want to see is the vendor-specific vGPU
 > types/names leaking out into the user-facing interface via a trait
 > or (worse) a custom resource class on flavors.

How do you expect users to actually use this then? If I have a CUDA application, I need to boot an instance with not only an nvidia CPU, but likely a very specific model or range of them. If I get an instance with an AMD GPU, not only do I not have drivers for it, but I don't have libraries or application code that can use it.

 > For example, a user will want to specify that they want one VGPU
 > resource class with the following standard traits:
 > 
 > * HW_GPU_RESOLUTION_W3840H2160
 > * HW_GPU_MAX_DISPLAY_HEADS_2
 > * HW_GPU_API_DXVA
 > * HW_GPU_API_OPENGL_V4_5

This may be enough detail for me to run a VDI instance, but I don't think it's going to even remotely address the need from the GPGPU crowd.

 > There are a number of Nvidia vGPU types that would meet the above
 > requirements: M60-8Q, M60-4Q, M6-8Q, M6-4Q.
 > 
 > How are you planning to expose the actual capabilities (the traits)
 > instead of vendor product IDs?

I don't think we need to expose PCI-style vendor/model pairs in traits, but I do expect we're going to need to expose things like "nvidia" and "M60". If we don't people will just have to throw those traits on the devices themselves, which is not going to look good.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2018-05-15 14:38:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> > Obviously, I'd prefer to have a YAML-based way of providing
 > > inventory and host device information, but we're not going to go
 > > that route.
 > >
 > > The thing I do *not* want to see is the vendor-specific vGPU
 > > types/names leaking out into the user-facing interface via a
 > trait
 > > or (worse) a custom resource class on flavors.
 > 
 > How do you expect users to actually use this then? If I have a CUDA
 > application, I need to boot an instance with not only an nvidia
 > CPU, but likely a very specific model or range of them. If I get an
 > instance with an AMD GPU, not only do I not have drivers for it,
 > but I don't have libraries or application code that can use it.

We have traits for CUDA and OpenCL etc already.

 > > For example, a user will want to specify that they want one VGPU
 > > resource class with the following standard traits:
 > >
 > > * HW_GPU_RESOLUTION_W3840H2160
 > > * HW_GPU_MAX_DISPLAY_HEADS_2
 > > * HW_GPU_API_DXVA
 > > * HW_GPU_API_OPENGL_V4_5
 > 
 > This may be enough detail for me to run a VDI instance, but I don't
 > think it's going to even remotely address the need from the GPGPU
 > crowd.
 > 
 > > There are a number of Nvidia vGPU types that would meet the above
 > > requirements: M60-8Q, M60-4Q, M6-8Q, M6-4Q.
 > >
 > > How are you planning to expose the actual capabilities (the
 > traits)
 > > instead of vendor product IDs?
 > 
 > I don't think we need to expose PCI-style vendor/model pairs in
 > traits, but I do expect we're going to need to expose things like
 > "nvidia" and "M60". If we don't people will just have to throw
 > those traits on the devices themselves, which is not going to look
 > good.

"nvidia" and "M60" are exactly the things I am trying *not* to leak out to users.'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2018-05-17 14:09:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2018-05-23 21:32:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2018-05-30 17:29:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Jay: How would the user be able to ensure that their guest image has suitable drivers if the hardware details aren't exposed?"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2018-05-30 18:32:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> Jay: How would the user be able to ensure that their guest image
 > has suitable drivers if the hardware details aren't exposed?

Chris, which of the standardized GPU traits already in os_traits would *not* be enough for a user to specify the workload's requirements?

https://github.com/openstack/os-traits/blob/master/os_traits/hw/gpu/api.py
https://github.com/openstack/os-traits/blob/master/os_traits/hw/gpu/max_display_heads.py
https://github.com/openstack/os-traits/blob/master/os_traits/hw/gpu/resolution.py

-jay"}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2018-05-30 21:34:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Jay: I've never actually done this, so maybe I'm just missing something.  Suppose I have a linux guest and want to do some GPGPU processing.  How do I know whether I need the GRID
vPC driver, the Quadro vDWS driver, the GRID
vApps driver, or the legacy GRID K1/K2/etc driver?  How do I specify the amount of vGPU RAM I need?  (i.e. the difference between the M60-8Q with 8GB and the M60-4Q with 4GB where the resolution and # of virtual display heads are the same)"}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2018-05-31 12:13:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Jay, while I understand your concerns about traits, I left a node explaining people should set the traits using osc-placement, so that this spec is not really related about this.

Of course, we could add yet another config option for asking the operators to set the traits by nova.conf but I'd prefer to wait for having a YAML file just for that. So, please, could you please review this spec without the traits concern, and just accept to leave operators to either use custom traits or the already standard GPU ones (like CUDA versions ones ) ?"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2018-05-31 15:33:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> Jay: I've never actually done this, so maybe I'm just missing
 > something.  Suppose I have a linux guest and want to do some GPGPU
 > processing.  How do I know whether I need the GRID
 > vPC driver, the Quadro vDWS driver, the GRID
 > vApps driver, or the legacy GRID K1/K2/etc driver?

Because your code would be written using a supported version of one of the various parallel computing platforms -- i.e. OpenACC, OpenCL, or whatever. Those are the traits that are listed in the os_traits library. If there are more traits needed to differentiate *capabilities* of a particular provider of VGPU functionality, then let's add those to os_traits and not come up with yet another vendor-centric landfill.

 >  How do I
 > specify the amount of vGPU RAM I need?  (i.e. the difference
 > between the M60-8Q with 8GB and the M60-4Q with 4GB where the
 > resolution and # of virtual display heads are the same)

If that is truly a consumable resource (not sold on that yet, since # display heads turned out to not actually be a consumable resource), then it would be a separate resource class. If not, it should be a trait in os-traits."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2018-05-31 16:41:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(12 comments)

Strong -1 from me on this.

My biggest points:

1) This should be NVIDIA specific -- since vGPU types only apply to NVIDIA products. I can find no mention of vGPU types for any other vendor. Intel's GVT-g technology has a "GVT resource management" layer that refers to vGPU types but, yes, you guessed it, those vGPU types are just NVIDIA vGPU types exposed via the /sysfs/.../mdev_supported_types file. This makes sense since it was NVIDIA that contributed the mdev framework to the linux kernel to "standardize" what is essentially their own technology. But I digress...

2) There should be no mention of custom traits. If more traits are needed to describe vGPU capabilities, they should be added to os-traits.

3) The spec should stay on point that the problem being solved is specifically this:

"An operator needs a way to inform the libvirt driver which NVIDIA vGPU types an NVIDIA physical GPU is configured to accept."

BTW, I still don't see why we shouldn't basically have a big hash table of NVIDIA product names (vGPU types) to lists of os-traits capabilities that match to that NVIDIA product name. We could house that in /nova/virt/vgpu_capabilities.py and let all the virt drivers use it. And that would solve the problem domain of "how can I map a user's request for some capabilities and resources to a provider of those resources".

-jay'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2018-06-01 16:26:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2018-06-05 13:39:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Note however, actually getting this merged is going to be dependent on the whole "placement migrate the worldview" spec and implementation...

commit_message:
Add python3 django 1.11 job instead of django 2.0 job

Django 2.0 is now used in tox py35 job, so there is no need for
py35dj20 job. Instead, Django 1.11 with python3 is not covered.

- py35dj20 job is dropped from tox.ini.
- python3-django111 is added to tox.ini.
  python3 is specified to basepython to avoid a specific python version.
- Zuul job to consume python3-django111 is added.

Note that horizon-openstack-tox-py35dj20 cannot be dropped
because this job is used by horizon plugins.

Change-Id: Ic3b5e06d591a6f1d667993d19dcddfaf40882dee

Add fast_forward_upgrade_tasks in ironic services.

Ironic services already present in Newton release,
ironic-api and ironic-conductor, are missing their
fast_forward_upgrade_tasks section.

commit_message:
Fix the wrong status of firewalls

add callback function. When a router is deleted, the function will be
called to update the firewalls after router is deleted. Fix the wrong
status of the firewall when a router is deleted which is the only one
that associated with firewalls

Change-Id: Ie567c965e4a4d4764c7274b2242327056a934c62
Closes-Bug: #1742872

[{'created': '2018-06-06 20:07:05.000000000', 'message': 'fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: Iceeaad2d6e31f3afeba5879ba3825caba437940d
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>
'}]
commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: Iceeaad2d6e31f3afeba5879ba3825caba437940d
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Register the collect_timing keystone_authtoken option

Icf00c66f57d20d2cef724c233160d3b1e0d52102 introduced a new option to
keystoneauth1.loading. This adds that option to make Mistral happy.
Also adds split_loggers.

Change-Id: Ifac7617decc2990ff87b76d39bf0f72a61ff2b99
Closes-Bug: #1775140

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: Ie62663550431ec392baf920152063a6a3e3b2c57
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

[{'created': '2018-01-22 13:37:47.000000000', 'message': 'Fix race condition with enabling SG on many ports at once

When there is many calls to enable security groups on ports there
can be sometimes race contition with between refresh recource_cache
with data get by "pull" call to neutron server and data received
with "push" rpc message from neutron server.
In such case when "push" message comes with information about
updated port (with enabled port_security), in local cache this port
is already updated so local AFTER_UPDATE call is not called for

writing new values directly to resource_cache._type_cache dict.
Due to that if resource will be updated during "pull" call to neutron
server, local AFTER_UPDATE will still be triggered for such resource.

   group so RemoteResourceCache don't trigger local notification about
   port AFTER UPDATE and L2 agent don't know that security groups for this
   port should be changed

resource_cache.

writing new values directly to resource_cache._type_cache dict.

commit_message:
Fix race condition with enabling SG on many ports at once

When there are many calls to enable security groups on ports there
can be sometimes race condition between refresh recource_cache
with data get by "pull" call to neutron server and data received
with "push" rpc message from neutron server.
In such case when "push" message comes with information about
updated port (with enabled port_security), in local cache this port
is already updated so local AFTER_UPDATE call is not called for
such port and its rules in firewall are not updated.

It happend quite often in fullstack security groups test because
there are 4 ports created in this test and all 4 are updated to
apply SG to it one by one.
And here's what happen then in details:
1. port 1 was updated in neutron-server so it sends push notification
   to L2 agent to update security groups,
2. port 1 info was saved in resource cache on L2 agent's side and agent
   started to configure security groups for this port,
3. as one of steps L2 agent called
   SecurityGroupServerAPIShim._select_ips_for_remote_group() method;
   In that method RemoteResourceCache.get_resources() is called and this
   method asks neutron-server for details about ports from given
   security_group,
4. in the meantime neutron-server got port update call for second port
   (with same security group) so it sends to L2 agent informations about 2
   ports (as a reply to request sent from L2 agent in step 3),
5. resource cache updates informations about two ports in local cache,
   returns its data to
   SecurityGroupServerAPIShim._select_ips_for_remote_group() and all
   looks fine,
6. but now L2 agent receives push notification with info that port 2 is
   updated (changed security groups), so it checks info about this port
   in local cache,
7. in local cache info about port 2 is already WITH updated security
   group so RemoteResourceCache doesn't trigger local notification about
   port AFTER UPDATE and L2 agent doesn't know that security groups for this
   port should be changed

This patch fixes it by changing way how items are updated in
the resource_cache.
For now it is done with record_resource_update() method instead of
writing new values directly to resource_cache._type_cache dict.
Due to that if resource will be updated during "pull" call to neutron
server, local AFTER_UPDATE will still be triggered for such resource.

Change-Id: I5a62cc5731c5ba571506a3aa26303a1b0290d37b
Closes-Bug: #1742401

commit_message:
Disable update of containers for OpenShift deployments

The containers available upstream are not rebuilt that frequently, so
updating them in CI takes way too much time and resources in each job.

Pass the variable on the ansible command line to ensure it is not
overriden by one of the environment files such as:

commit_message:
[Scenario tests] Try longer SSH timeout for ubuntu image

It looks that many scenario tests are failing because of too long
instance booting time and reached ssh timeout during checking
connectivity.
So longer timeout should solve this problem and tests should
not fail with this reason.

Change-Id: I5d0678ea2383483e6106976c148353ef4352befd
Closes-Bug: #1754327

commit_message:
Strip signed certificate

Certificate (ca.crt) has to be striped for some application parsers
as they might require pure base64 representation of
certificate itself, without empty characters
at the beginning nor the end of file

Change-Id: I85457e0e2adcf21003300fafc6e2502f74b1afb5
(cherry picked from commit 69ffdae1d0cd0a5f24a0b6411afe1a91f175cd79)

commit_message:
Use the standard messaging in the plan_management workbook

Update the plan_management workbook to use the standard message sending
workflow. This workflow reduces the boilerplate that is copied between
workflows by defining the message structure, providing the retry logic
and ensuring the task on a "FAILED" message.

The workflow also offers optional persistence in Swift. If the plan name
is given to the workflow it will store the messages in a Swift container
named <plan_name>-messages.

Related-Bug: #1757372
Change-Id: I9755eaa6621ec1d83fe98e20445a4f13b4ea0686

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I716ec44a6dd6d14f1ac221e058f365b8d44fb423
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I6d30f89428fc232a5ee0f20507273368f3bfa8b0
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
[Fullstack] Add block test until IPs will be really configured

In securitygroups fullstack test dhcp agent is used to configure
IP addresses inside FakeMachines.
During preparation to test, when such fake vms are created,
they are only blocked until boot - so until port becomes ACTIVE
in Neutron's database.
This patch adds also blocking vms until IP address is really
configured on each of such VMs.
If IP address will be not configured then we should at least have
better error message then error that nc process cannot be started.

Change-Id: I709b1489132edba932a4c73bea60f810c26011fa
Related-Bug: #1744402

commit_message:
Introduce Cyborg Resource Quota -- Usage Part

The concept of quota gives the possibility to limit the maximum number of
acceleration resources that one project/tenant can prossess.
It will also  give the admin users the ability to increase the resource count
on-demand, given that the system constraints are not exceeded.

Change-Id: I9ed3ec06290246ba7365eaeb97a5c4fc2916f538

[{'created': '2018-06-06 11:56:57.000000000', 'message': '[Fullstack] Change time waiting for async ping results

During agents restart there is async ping run and there is
called function to wait until all async ping workers will
finish their job.

In TestHAL3Agent.test_ha_router_restart_agents_no_packet_lost
there is 60 pings send with 1 second timeout so default
wait_until_true timeout which is set to 60 seconds might not
be enough in some cases.
Because of that wait_until_true timeout is now set as
number_of_pings to send * ping_timeout + 1

This "+1 second" should give enough time to finish all workers.

Change-Id: Ia7c3755c2ba5029bdab3c1dd30b305f3bde19740
Closes-Bug: #1775183
'}, {'created': '2018-06-06 13:29:01.000000000', 'message': '[Fullstack] Change time waiting for async ping results

During agents restart there is async ping run and there is
called function to wait until all async ping workers will
finish their job.

In TestHAL3Agent.test_ha_router_restart_agents_no_packet_lost
there are 60 pings sent with 1 second timeout so default
wait_until_true timeout which is set to 60 seconds might not
be enough in some cases.
Because of that wait_until_true timeout is now set as
twice higher value than is needed to number of packets to send
with ping_timeout.

This should give enough time to finish all workers.

Change-Id: Ia7c3755c2ba5029bdab3c1dd30b305f3bde19740
Closes-Bug: #1775183
'}]
commit_message:
[Fullstack] Change time waiting for async ping results

During agents restart there is async ping run and there is
called function to wait until all async ping workers will
finish their job.

In TestHAL3Agent.test_ha_router_restart_agents_no_packet_lost
there are 60 pings sent with 1 second timeout so default
wait_until_true timeout which is set to 60 seconds might not
be enough in some cases.
Because of that wait_until_true timeout is now set as
twice higher value than is needed to number of packets to send
with ping_timeout.

This should give enough time to finish all workers.

Change-Id: Ia7c3755c2ba5029bdab3c1dd30b305f3bde19740
Closes-Bug: #1775183

commit_message:
Disable SSL messaging for neutron

For some reason, messaging over SSL is not working for neutron-server.
This is blocking integrated repo patches, so to unblock the repo while
the root cause is figured out, we disable SSL for now.

Change-Id: I0634644f7effe729b64489885fdb6b50dc68a911

commit_message:
Add a hook for restore process to check if successful

1.This is the same solution with the backup process. Previously we only
check the stderr of the restore command, but this method is not
reliable, and the changes during percona-xtrabackup 2.4.11:
https://jira.percona.com/browse/PXB-1542
causes the gate jobs failed in creating a slave MySQL instance.

The new hook currently is only used by InnoBackupEx restore runner with
checking the exit status and stderr output of xbstream.

2.with[1] merged,this makes DIB_CLOUD_IMAGES more flexible, but it
break trovestack build image, now we need to specify a more
detailed path to DIB_CLOUD_IMAGES to get the appropriate content.

[1]:https://review.openstack.org/#/c/568697/

Co-Authored-By: Zhao Chao <zhaochao1984@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: zhanggang <zhanggang@cmss.chinamobile.com>
Co-Authored-By: jiansong <jian.song@easystack.cn>

Change-Id: I4e1e4401d40a664ab7fbba5bc08e13884cca06c2

commit_message:
Expose instance_get_all_uuids_by_host() from DB API and use it

We've had a long-standing optimization point in the
InstanceList.get_uuids_by_host() method, where we pull the entire
list of instance objects only to strip and return the uuids. We
already had a query method for generating just the uuids in the
DB API, but it was not exposed as it was just a helper for another
method. This exposes it publicly and uses it in that InstanceList
method.

Change-Id: I35c05e78d59ec9b95c2a443979b8d66cd42ea043

commit_message:
Make instance.refresh() avoid recursion better

The instance.refresh() method is careful to prevent recursion, to avoid
lazy-loads on the object we just pulled from the database. However, it
was allowing those to raise OrphanedObjectError to the caller to make
them visible. The caller is not really at fault in that case, and can not
avoid it.

The only time this has ever come up is in the context of cellsv1 and the
keypairs field that it doesn't have set on instances in the child cells.
Thus, this changes refresh() to just skip fields that are set on the
current object and unset on the one we pull from the database, as we
would not be able to refresh those anyway. This logs the situation so that
it is visible (at DEBUG) if it becomes relevant.

Change-Id: Ibfca4ae922766b5b977e217594d12e1169ddeee8

to 'ipa-server-install'. Let's introduce the 'ipa_server_install_params'

commit_message:
Introduce a custom parameter to pass to ipa-server-install

Sometimes it would be nice to be able to pass extra parameters
to 'ipa-server-install'. Let's introduce the 'ipa_server_install_params'
parameter which will be passed as extra arguments to the freeipa
installation.

One of the use cases is being able to disable dnssec validation
(via the '--no-dnssec-validation' parameter)

Change-Id: I0b8d985b6442a183251d1c2a47a91fc2f5d0f978

commit_message:
Add logstash filters

This adds the ability to include logstash log parsing filters for
various openstack and service logs.  These filters are disabled by
default and can be enabled by toggling the deploy_logstash_filters
variable.

Change-Id: I5c46f78f232d3fb604283ae623cd3975a8346c7c

subject: Update Heat template version
messages:
[{'account_id': 26222, 'date': '2018-06-04 08:39:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 26222, 'date': '2018-06-04 11:44:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 26222, 'date': '2018-06-04 12:12:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Patch Set 2 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 26222, 'date': '2018-06-04 12:13:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2018-06-04 14:55:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I agree in principle that the template version needs to be updated, but I'm concerned that jumping straight to Queens will have negative impacts on older deployments.

What does Heat do with a "future"/unsupported version?  Can you run a Queens template on a Newton deployment?

This really raises a few larger issues:

 - should the user be able to specify the desired Heat template version?

- should Heat Translator take the version into account when generating the template?

- How do we map TOSCA functionality to specific HOT versions?

- If we agree that the default template version should be changed, what should the new default be?'}, {'account_id': 26222, 'date': '2018-06-05 01:44:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Bobh,
I think if user can choose version of heat, that she/he want, it will be better. IMO, using heat-translator version can solve above problem.

I will update this part to follow the best solution.'}, {'account_id': 26222, 'date': '2018-06-05 15:53:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I added new patch in Tosca-parser, where hot_template_version locate in metadata. Can you guys look at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/572453 and give me some advice? Thank you.'}, {'account_id': 6456, 'date': '2018-06-07 02:31:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Yes, agree that having this done accordingly patch 572453 is good idea, just changing version to latest probably can create problem Bob mentioned. Thanks1'}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2018-06-07 16:44:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The more I think about this the more I wonder what the benefits are.

Later HOT template versions provide access to additional methods and resources.  However TOSCA provides a limited number of intrinsic functions, and TOSCA Parser only supports a subset of those, so I don't see how changing the HOT template version will affect anything.  If the "new" HOT method doesn't have a corresponding intrinsic function defined in TOSCA, it's not going to be able to be used in the TOSCA template anyway.

I do think that specifying and passing through the HOT version is a reasonable thing to do, I just don't see how it's going to be useful in practice.

Do you have an example of a scenario that would use this functionality?'}, {'account_id': 26222, 'date': '2018-06-08 02:46:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi Bobh,

I think we should keep the 2013 version, but we should let users to choose the version they want. Because when I process HOT template, some functions don't work with the older version."}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2018-06-08 03:16:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Do you have an example of a TOSCA template that can be parsed by TOSCA Parser but cannot be deployed because heat-translator generates functions that don't work with the 2013 version?

I'm still struggling to understand how it's possible to use any of the later functions in a TOSCA template that can only have a specific set of intrinsic functions that are supported by TOSCA Parser."}]

commit_message:
Update Heat template version

This patch updates heat template version from version
'2013-05-23' to '2018-03-02'. In new version, Heat translator
can support more features.

Change-Id: I1ae1218fc617e1b83d4bce3d00d4fd1920ec5b17

commit_message:
Specification for Cyborg Agent-Driver API.

Enhanced the device description model (which is structured
as a Python dictionary) to align it with RCs and traits
that are published by Cyborg in Nova.

Change-Id: I27a4bcab6379652e6893aee7fcc684036db93d61
Proposes: spec cyborg-agent-driver-api

commit_message:
Rename test files to test_* pattern

We're going to switch to default Django test runner by default.
This patch renames test files to make tests descoverable by
Nose and Django test runners without addidional configuration.

Related blueprint: improve-horizon-testing

Change-Id: If4ee8dcd173c2f331bf34cf93c489029489c63ea

commit_message:
Increase accuracy of detecting apache install

The javascript-common package includes /etc/apache2/conf-available/javascript-common.conf
so it is not sufficiuent to use the presence of the /etc/apache2
directory as an indicator of apache being installed

Change-Id: Ia5c80b9842b0c9633d7ccda2837597d94d098df3

commit_message:
Bypass pip constraints when installing Elastic Curator

The elasticsearch-curator package requires certifi 2018.4.16 but this
is constrained to version 2018.1.18. Use isolated mode to allow
installation of the upstream version.

Change-Id: I4ba387afab35230e70b45fab42b6bfaf9ffeba19

commit_message:
ovn: Add dns_servers configuration support

networking-ovn optionally expects list of dns server to be defined in the
config -'ovn/dns_servers'. These will be included in the 'dns_server' DHCP
option field when the VMs send DHCP request if the subnet's dns_nameservers field
is not defined by the user.

Change-Id: I353ac905069ecc945720df2b9e3051989238a02a
Partial-bug: #1774052

commit_message:
Fix share-service VM restart problem

The /etc/mtab file may have mount information such as 'nfsd'
that if copied to /etc/fstab will cause the share server to
hang when rebooted.

Update /etc/fstab with exactly the newly mounted or unmounted
shares rather than simply overwriting /etc/fstab with /etc/mtab.

Change-Id: I67602bae1f928769d768008deca7bd0f2fef1ac2
Close-Bug: #1639662
(cherry picked from commit b76934770b0f42950cad35a3e2a5a8e060462332)

Fix workflow-list error when fields filter is added

When I run 'mistral workflow-list --filter fields=XXX', I always get
error like 'workflow object has no attribute XXX'. So I make some change
to solve it.

I think the metadata passthrough case is pretty simple if you want to just get something in now, but as noted you don't get the API validation for that, and you're really need to provide something above Nova to do that validation for users before it hits the API, either via some library, wrapper API service, or CLI."}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-03-13 13:46:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Workflow-1

Thanks for your comments, Matt! 

I'm going to take a closer look at Mogan and see whether it makes sense to propose a similar spec there. To be honest, I had not even heard about that project until very recently. I totally get that you don't want to change the API to implement a specific use case for essentially one virt driver. FWIW, the only reason I proposed this to Nova in the first place is that it currently is the entry point for users who boot baremetal instances, whether we want that or not.

WIP, until I get feedback from Mogan folks / take a closer look at the project."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-03-13 14:38:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Ironic works quite well standalone, so the only point of this effort is to enable Nova users to use advanced features from Ironic. Specifically, users that have hybrid deployments will not benefit from anything developed outside of Nova.'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-03-13 15:06:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

>>> Ironic works quite well standalone, so the only point of this effort is to enable Nova users to use advanced features from Ironic. Specifically, users that have hybrid deployments will not benefit from anything developed outside of Nova.

Sure, but Nova is still needed for scheduling / quota usages accounting, etc.  That's what I meant by "entry point" - a high level API for end users, i.e. "provision one ironic.silver using image X" rather than "provision the specific baremetal server S using image X".'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-03-13 15:14:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Exactly, that's why I think this spec is needed (if we want RAID to be exposed to many more users than it is now)"}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2017-03-14 04:54:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Thanks Matt!

From Mogan's perspective, we think baremetal in nova is "high performance vm", Nova doesn't really provide bare metal instance. Users will get an instance
based on the flavor(vcpus, memory, disks) size within the request, they don't care about whether it's a vm or a baremetal, they just need the compute resources.
So such baremetal specific features like RAID should not be added in Nova, which will make the API and model more complex, and if you really want baremetal, you
may also confused about why it's vcpu, vm_state..., you may also want to change these as well.

Mogan is for users who really want baremetal instance, it's not conflict with the current Nova+Ironic way, And maybe in a hybrid deployment we can have both
Nova+KVM+Ironic and Mogan+Ironic. With Nova, Ironic acts as a virt driver and expose baremetal as a high performance vm to users. With Mogan it provides full
baremetal capabilities to users.

And most cloud providers deliver vm and baremetal services separately with different capabilities instead of just one compute service.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-03-14 10:23:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Zhenguo, it looks like you're trying to decide on user's behalf :/ What  I hear again and again on summits and in private conversations is that people are applying downstream hacks to ironic and/or nova to make deploy-time RAID (also software RAID and partitioning) to work with ironic+nova pair. Hence this proposal.

I'm not sure what is production story around Mogan now. But I'm pretty sure at least some users will not find using different API for virtual and baremetal instances acceptable.

Essentially, rejecting this proposal will leave users with either downstream hacks, or somehow using Ironic API directly (which is now possible thanks to policy work)."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2017-03-14 11:02:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Go some ideas on more possible other ways of doing this, when looking at the general trait issues.'}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2017-03-14 12:16:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Dmitry, I think the downstream hacks are just because there is no other choice, as OpenStack just have one compute service. And there are also downstream hacks for vmware and powervm to make their advanced capabilities available from Nova. I'm not sure if Nova will accept all these single-driver specific features. As I understand, without changing the API, deploy-time RAID will be very convoluted and maybe not expose all the capabilities. Definitely I can't decide what nova or ironic do, I just want to propose another option for directly baremetal instance management which makes things more easy. And seems there's no compelling reason for using one set of API to manage both VMs and baremetals. Mogan is still a very new project, but it will somewhat solve all problems."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-03-14 12:21:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

> And seems there's no compelling reason for using one set of API to manage both VMs and baremetals

Nothing can be further from the truth for so many (majority?) of people! There are lots of compelling reasons, like reusing existing tooling, avoiding code duplication or deployer's simplicity.

But let's not go there. The goal of this spec is to extend Nova-Ironic integration. It may be rejected for good reasons, but let's not reject it on the basis that another project may implement something similar."}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2017-03-14 12:34:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Dmitry, sorry, I don't mean to reject this, the reason that I participate the discussion is because the comments about Mogan in Alternatives of this spec. So please go ahead with Nova guys comments."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2017-03-14 14:43:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(1 comment)

Is this one of those cases where cloud-init is really the thing we should be considering? It feels like from the Nova side what you actually want to express is "I need something with X disks" and then some script loaded through cloud init that does stuff with them. Because the minute you put RAID as a top level construct, you'll next need to put ZFS as a top level construct, and this becomes a pretty bad leaky abstraction.

Whereas if this was flavor oriented, so that ironic-platinum was going to give you 0+1 under the covers (but really just be about some dedicated IO pattern) it would be much more in line with what most users want to express.'}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2017-03-14 14:45:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

AFAIK, people want to put / on a hardware RAID and such, which AFAIK cloud-init can't help much with."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2017-03-14 15:06:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

> Is this one of those cases where cloud-init is really the thing we should be considering

May work for software RAID, but definitely not hardware one.'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-03-14 16:10:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(7 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-03-14 16:16:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

> Is this one of those cases where cloud-init is really the thing we should be considering?

Even if it was a software RAID, how this would work for configuring RAID for the root disk?

> It feels like from the Nova side what you actually want to express is "I need something with X disks" and then some script loaded through cloud init that does stuff with them.

I guess we could do that with user_data + ironic-python-agent, but the point of making it a concept of the API was so that we could give proper messages early in the API layer.'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-03-14 16:19:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Thanks, Zhenguo! I should at least mention Mogan as one of the alternatives.'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-03-31 08:00:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: -Workflow'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-04-03 15:26:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

(3 comments)

Folks,

Thank you for your feedback! I've tried to incorporate your comments to the spec overall and specifically to the `Alternatives` section.

BDM seemed to be the most natural place to put this, if we wanted to make RAID a concept of the API (to make it clean to end users, provide good error messaging, etc). But, if there is strong push back on changes to BDM, I hope we can choose one of the alternatives and proceed with that. Personally, I'm leaning towards using of metadata + predefined configs in flavor extra specs.

Please comment on the alternatives you prefer.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-04-03 15:26:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-04-03 15:33:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Verified+1

- gate-nova-specs-pep8-ubuntu-xenial http://logs.openstack.org/51/408151/8/check/gate-nova-specs-pep8-ubuntu-xenial/1db6ea9/ : SUCCESS in 2m 12s
- gate-nova-specs-python27-ubuntu-xenial http://logs.openstack.org/51/408151/8/check/gate-nova-specs-python27-ubuntu-xenial/7a2458b/ : SUCCESS in 3m 51s'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2017-04-04 13:56:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-04-04 16:25:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-04-04 18:24:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Something that was missing from this for me, while reading, was a picture of what the Ironic side looked like. I spent the first few minutes thinking that perhaps an ironic custom resource class could capture the desired stuff: essentially the resource class describes a baremetal with associated raid controller and disks.

It was only later that I realized that this is trying to present the existence of the raid controller and disks as a blank slate upon which we can express a desired config and requirements (RAID 5 with 5 disks of N-GB) and not only will we select the right piece of hardware, but that hardware will also be told to configure itself appropriately.

That could get a bit complicated. Do we also want to be able to say I only want a RAID controller that has the following features, and this amount of cache and can guarantee performance X?

But it may be that I'm thinking about this too much through a resource providers lens?

In any case it seems there could be a lot of edge cases here."}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-04-05 08:27:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Chris,

>>> It was only later that I realized that this is trying to present the existence of the raid controller and disks as a blank slate upon which we can express a desired config and requirements (RAID 5 with 5 disks of N-GB) and not only will we select the right piece of hardware, but that hardware will also be told to configure itself appropriately.

Exactly, the idea is to allow this level of flexibility.

>>> That could get a bit complicated. Do we also want to be able to say I only want a RAID controller that has the following features, and this amount of cache and can guarantee performance X?

If I understand your point correctly, that sounds like a scheduling question to me: you only want to end up on an eligible node, you do not ask Nova/Ironic to configure a specific RAID for you. IMO, we could implement this by requiring traits in flavor extra specs, so that "amount of cache" or "guarantee of performance X" would be such traits on the Ironic resource providers.

>>> But it may be that I'm thinking about this too much through a resource providers lens?

No, it's a good point actually. As I mentioned in the reply to Sean, this spec has omitted this (scheduling) part of the problem and has been focused only on the expressing a configuration of a desired RAID so far. Perhaps it needs to discuss both or explicitly say that scheduling is a separate concern.

Thank you!'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-04-05 09:26:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

> If I understand your point correctly, that sounds like a scheduling
 > question to me: you only want to end up on an eligible node, you do
 > not ask Nova/Ironic to configure a specific RAID for you. IMO, we
 > could implement this by requiring traits in flavor extra specs, so
 > that "amount of cache" or "guarantee of performance X" would be
 > such traits on the Ironic resource providers.

Your response is part of why it's complicated. You've used the term "trait" with phrases that have variable quantitative values. I can 10GB of cache, or 512MB. I can guarantee reads of x or 20x, or anywhere in between. Those could be considered resource classes, then, because they are quantitative.

There are a great many dimensions, both qualitative and quantitative, on which this stuff can be described but there could be a mismatch between how something describes what it can do, and how it is consumed: we want to choose it based on how it is described, but we want to consume just one of it (because it's physical). This suggests something a bit like nested resource providers.

Unfortunately I don't think we can fully separate the scheduling and configuration aspects because we want to be sure that we are representing state in the same or at least translatable forms in both situations.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2017-04-05 13:41:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2017-04-05 13:48:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

I think we need to table this until this forum session:

http://forumtopics.openstack.org/cfp/details/16

Which yes puts this out past pike since it's past the spec freeze, but I don't see us reaching agreement on this anytime soon since I'm -2 on using BDMs for this."}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-04-06 14:09:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Matt,

I got that you are totally against the BDMs :) I was hoping we could pick one of the described alternatives and change the spec accordingly.

If you guys talk about this at the forum, please put the outcomes of the discussion as comments to the spec. Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2017-05-16 11:45:18.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Ironic: add support for instance RAID configuration

Users of Ironic virt driver want to be able to configure a RAID on
boot of a new instance. As Ironic is currently an admin-only API, it
should be possible to provide a RAID configuration via OpenStack
Compute API to be used by Ironic (or, possibly in the future,
any other) virt driver.

APIImpact

Change-Id: I25de6e794b1f0046c350f499699da305ce9468a4

[{'created': '2018-03-27 08:30:28.000000000', 'message': 'VMAX driver - Enable multiattach support

Support multiattach capability with Dell EMC VMAX arrays.

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I47def751d6718e167ace9dd4169b8a4a87052a9a

'}]
commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I47def751d6718e167ace9dd4169b8a4a87052a9a
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-15 01:01:55.000000000', 'message': "Support relay RP for allocation candidates

When the compute node resource provider has no requested resource
itself and can provide them with combination of multiple sharing
resource providers, AllocationCandidates.get_by_filters didn't
return the combination if the sharing providers are in different
aggregations associated to the compute node.

To fix the bug, this patch changes the function of
_alloc_candidates_with_shared() to add non-sharing-provider to the
provider summaries if it can provide the resource with sharing
providers and to extract allocation request from non-sharing provider
only when it can supply requested resources.

Change-Id: I332fa33c320a697136d6f0994fbad573a31eda1b
Closes-Bug: #1732731

commit_message:
Support relay RP for allocation candidates

When the compute node resource provider has no requested resource
itself and can provide them with combination of multiple sharing
resource providers, AllocationCandidates.get_by_filters didn't
return the combination if the sharing providers are in different
aggregations associated to the compute node.

To fix the bug, this patch changes _alloc_candidates_with_shared()
function to build allocation request from non-sharing provider
regardress of whether it has requested resources for its own or
not.

Change-Id: I332fa33c320a697136d6f0994fbad573a31eda1b
Partial-Bug: #1732731

commit_message:
update constraint for oslo.utils to new release 3.28.3

add stestr to upper-constraints.txt and global-requirements.txt

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/563394/ brought in os-testr-1.0.0
os-testr brought in stestr, which is unconstrained in pike
this causes installs of os-testr-1.0.0 to install stestr-1.3.0 (latest)
stestr-1.3.0 is not co-installable on pike, it needs python-subunit>=1.3.0
python-subunit is constrained to 1.2.0 on pike.

Change-Id: Ia37d4230d18d396692f66925e754fb87ec0eb21b

subject: fix pep8 errors under python 3
revisions:
[{'created': '2018-06-06 21:24:30.000000000', 'message': "fix pep8 errors under python 3

Under python 3 'print' is a function, and the linter does not like
having a space between the function name and the paren indicating the
call. Remove the space.

The builtin 'file' is removed under python 3. Replace its use with
'open', which is available on both python 2 and 3.

Change-Id: Ib8522d8ab1974a4ba3e407ffbe449e2f5fc9471a
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>
"}]
commit_message:
fix pep8 errors under python 3

Under python 3 'print' is a function, and the linter does not like
having a space between the function name and the paren indicating the
call. Remove the space.

The builtin 'file' is removed under python 3. Replace its use with
'open', which is available on both python 2 and 3.

Change-Id: Ib8522d8ab1974a4ba3e407ffbe449e2f5fc9471a

commit_message:
Delete request for non-existent ID will be 404.

When trying to delete a non-existent backup, action,
client, job, session it will raise exception with
HTTP response 404.

Closes-Bug: #1596935

commit_message:

Under Python 3 print is a function, and the linter does not want to

the call. Remove the space.

commit_message:
Add retry logic to post_lifecycle_hook_message

This patch adds retry logic to post_lifecycle_hook_message
when posting a lifecyle hook to Zaqar. This will make posting
messages to Zaqar more robust in the event Zaqar is unavailable.

Change-Id: I1681cf44a4c0a8bded21d328b9a7fff611355529

commit_message:
Added engine_name parameter to action creation.

With implementation of new engines (nova, rsync, ...) a regression was
introduced - user is no longer able to create working action for nova instance
backup because config generated by freezer-scheduler passed to freezer-agent
doesn't contain 'engine_name' thus falling back to default value 'tar'
even when 'mode' is set to 'nova'. This patch adds possibility to specify
'engine_name' in web UI which is then passed to freezer-scheduler job cfg.

Change-Id: Ifc4ed728db369da54fecef3c2ecf4dfcbfe4fefb

In case of HA routers IPv6 forwarding is not disabled by default and
then enabled only on master node.
Before this patch it was done in opposite way, so forwarding was

commit_message:
Disable IPv6 forwarding by default on HA routers

In case of HA routers IPv6 forwarding is not disabled by default and
then enabled only on master node.
Before this patch it was done in opposite way, so forwarding was
enabled by default and then disabled on backup nodes.
When forwarding was enabled/disabled for qg- port, MLDv2 packets are
sent and that might lead to temportary packets loss as packets to
FIP were sent to this backup node instead of master one.

Related-Bug: #1771841

Change-Id: Ia6b772e91c1f94612ca29d7082eca999372e60d6
(cherry picked from commit 3e9e2a5b4b2654864bb0e2a7d9b841eb03240147)

commit_message:
Enhanced KVM Storage QoS

blueprint enhanced-kvm-storage-qos

QEMU 1.7 provides options to specify maximum burst IOPS and maximum burst
bandwidth per disk. Additionally disk IO size can be specified as part of
this version of QEMU.

At the moment, the Nova libvirt driver does not support setting storage
burst IOPS limits. For this reason, some instances might exhaust
storage resources, impacting other tenants and applications.

Change-Id: Ic51231e3c0d5d01f479d1ca630abdfcd74ce6a07

commit_message:
WIP repurpose action container_images_prepare

Previously this action wrote an environment to the plan which
populates all image parameters with default values.

This commit changes that behaviour so that it now writes environment
files which populate the ContainerImagePrepare parameter, one file for
pulling from the default registry, and one file for uploading/pulling
from the undercloud registry.

This is marked as WIP as this will be the last change which triggers
the switchover to workflow-driven prepare by default.

Change-Id: I53f441b46474efcd80f8ee5f2e212c71982df400
Blueprint: container-prepare-workflow

commit_message:
convert windows line endings to unix format

Under python 3 the linter does not like line endings with \r\n so
replace them with just \n.

Change-Id: I6728ee3fc39a5b22ca06fcd9055872271ab79a53
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

Not sure why you think that the group add / remove service code is dead?  If it was indeed dead there is a bunch of other code, like in the API, that would need to be removed as well.  We do still allow the creation of custom groups, and the assignment of various services to those groups, though it can be dangerous and fraught with peril if done by someone who doesn't know what they are doing."}, {'account_id': 17386, 'date': '2018-06-07 21:08:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It's dead because the code to associate groups and services is via service addgroup / removegroup. I didn't change that. If you look in setup.cfg, there is no way for the cli to access the code I removed."}, {'account_id': 16520, 'date': '2018-06-07 21:21:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Yup, just spent some quality time digging through the code.  Don't love group apis calls being sort of proxied through the service command, but it looks like this is nothing new, and the help matches up to this usage."}]

[{'created': '2018-06-05 08:13:06.000000000', 'message': '[Fullstack] Wait for SG to be applied by L2 agent

In fullstack test_securitygroup there were used simple
net_helpers.assert_ping() and assert_not_ping() functions
which tries to ping IP address 3 times with some short timeout
and test fails if result of ping will not be as expected.

Unfortunately sometimes in fullstack tests it might be not enough
if test is creating new SG or SG rule or apply SG to port and
just after that checks connection because L2 agent don't have
enough time to apply all rules on "host".
This patch changes it to use block_until_ping() and
block_until_no_ping() methods from FakeMachine fixture.
It will also check if ping is possible/not possible but
will try to check it for 1 minute before fails.

Similar change is also done for methods which checks TCP
connectivity using netcat helper class. It now uses
common_utils.wait_until_true() helper function instead of
fail immediatelly.

commit_message:
[Fullstack] Wait for SG to be applied by L2 agent

In fullstack test_securitygroup there were used simple
net_helpers.assert_ping() and assert_not_ping() functions
which tries to ping IP address 3 times with some short timeout
and test fails if result of ping will not be as expected.

Unfortunately sometimes in fullstack tests it might be not enough
if test is creating new SG or SG rule or apply SG to port and
just after that checks connection because L2 agent don't have
enough time to apply all rules on "host".
This patch changes it to use block_until_ping() and
block_until_no_ping() methods from FakeMachine fixture.
It will also check if ping is possible/not possible but
will try to check it for 1 minute before fails.

Similar change is also done for methods which checks TCP
connectivity using netcat helper class. It now uses
common_utils.wait_until_true() helper function instead of
fail immediatelly.

Change-Id: I9e523d803e3c49d5d090ae5b9d36d43ce7311535
Closes-Bug: #1774006
Closes-Bug: #1767829

commit_message:
Move kata-run to this repo

We rename the job to kata-runsh to satisify the unique job name
constraint. This allows the job to be self testing with a depends on on
the github side PRs.

Some comments inline, I think I agree with Jay.

(4 comments)

Agree the default policy should be to disallow.  Otherwise, nits/questions.'}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2017-06-06 13:15:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

(1 comment)

I do agree with Jay that this is poor solution. For bit different reasons 'though.

With this change we're introducing backwards incompatible API change, which even worse is configurable so it will also introduce interoperability issues within the version, not just across versions. All this in name of security, which can be addressed in ways that does not do the same as idnetified in multiple alternative solutions. While all proposed alternatives are not optimal and perhaps even combination of them with some possible filtering on the purge command would make the situation better, I think any of the proposed alternatives are better than the proposed solution. All of the proposed alternatives also leaves room for further improvements without affecting user experience negatively while the policy will definitely introduce interoperability issues across opinionated deployments that are not going to go away.

We as a community have worked a lot over past years trying to make our APIs stable, backwards compatible, interoperable and secure. While policies are great way to not take the responsibility of everyones different opinions of security and instead putting that burden on deployers, operators and users, I think they are the single most stupid thing we have introduced what comes to the interoperability. Due to their nature of being undiscoverable they do cause huge amounts of trial and failure logic to anyone trying to develope tooling against our APIs and maintaining even our own client."}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-09-28 02:42:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-09-28 02:47:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1
