the new wording does not change my stance on this.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2017-09-28 18:28:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I get what Erno is saying, but my take is that this is OK.

It's not "backwards compatible" by default, but usually when we have to fix bugs like this, we don't want the broken behavior to stay compatible. I think having the policy control for this is a good compromise to make things more secure by default, while still allowing operators to override that behavior based on their own environment and needs. This makes it an explicit operator decision to potentially enable a security risk.

I do think it would be good to start a discussion with operators if that has not already happened. Maybe link to the openstack-operators thread if/when that happens.

As an alternative, I think option 2 wouldn't be too much of a risk, and I would hope that the conditions that lead to this are infrequent enough that it doesn't make that much of a difference. Giving operators a tool to clean out old deleted objects from the database is probably something that should be considered at some point anyway, as that can be an issue just over the normal lifespan of a cloud. That's not an issue limited to Glance either.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2017-09-28 18:30:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

May also be worth getting this on the agenda for the api-sig for discussion.'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-09-29 01:42:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I followed up on Tim Bell's suggestion from back in May and put together an operators' survey to get some data:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-operators/2017-September/014287.html"}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-09-29 02:10:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I followed up on Sean's suggestion and emailed the API-WG:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-September/122835.html

and the Interop-WG:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/interop-wg/2017-September/000193.html"}, {'account_id': 5490, 'date': '2017-09-29 08:00:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

We did not make use of assigning UUIDs to images and do not intend to in OpenTelekomCloud.

The clear rationale behind this is that a unique identifier should be exactly this: A 1:1 mapping to an image. If the image changes, it needs to have a new UUID.
(I just imagine what would happen if you could change the contents of a git commit ID without assigning a new ID -- hell would break lose as you can see in the discussions on SHA-1 collisions.)

Allowing a changed image with a previously used ID was a horrible hack in the first place.

Maybe there is a use case in a private cloud, where you have strange internal users that do pin image UUIDs because they believe things never should change and then you need to hack in a security patch without breaking your misconfigured automation ...

I would not have allowed reusing a image UUID for a changed image in our cloud. Never!

So yes, restricting this ability is the right direction. Not just for security reasons, but because the 1:1 mapping image content to image UUID must not be broken.

I can imagine the ability to specify image UUIDs to be useful when you create a clone for a cloud and want it to use the same UUIDs for images than the original. Not a frequent situation and operation. (Also I would still tell people they should reference images by name normally.)'}, {'account_id': 14495, 'date': '2017-09-29 09:13:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'd prefer to remove / deprecate this functionality completely. OTOH for existing clouds maybe some flexibility with policy setting would be the preferred approach."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2017-09-29 10:47:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I agree that this is a reasonable way to go. Various comments about that:

* From the api-sig standpoint this change is aligned with http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/api-wg/guidelines/api_interoperability.html . The severity of the problem is high enough that the fix ought to be backported as far as people are willing to go, thus the change is allowed to break all the rules.

* The policy handling maintains the ability for people who have really thought about it to maintain the bad behavior but defaults to a safer mode.

* It really is quite bad behavior, I agree with others that setting the id should be deprecated if some route to doing so can be found.

* The fix is sane, in the sense that it isn't really going to cause any surprises for people. In the past if you tried to set an image id there's was a chance it could fail because it is already in use. Now the failure mode is different and more frequent, but not completely out of the blue.

* Attempting to manage this on the purge side of things is fraught with error, people have the option to manage their purging directly on the database which will overcome any safeguards that tooling put in place. It's also feels very unhygienic to maintain a list of used ids.

* UUIDs are awesome and cheap."}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2017-09-29 11:23:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> The clear rationale behind this is that a unique identifier should
 > be exactly this: A 1:1 mapping to an image. If the image changes,
 > it needs to have a new UUID.

Totally agreed and the immutability promise needs to stay.

 > Allowing a changed image with a previously used ID was a horrible
 > hack in the first place.

Nope it's just a bug. Never was the intention.

 > I can imagine the ability to specify image UUIDs to be useful when
 > you create a clone for a cloud and want it to use the same UUIDs
 > for images than the original. Not a frequent situation and
 > operation. (Also I would still tell people they should reference
 > images by name normally.)

Si this is where it get hairy. Image name is by no means unique and thus with Images API v2 one can't even reference image by it's name anymore. There is actually increasing pressure to have loads of images with same name (Lifecycle management). As Glance is single zone service the ID is the only way to keep track of your images for any level of automation. Either your different clouds (or zones) have that one image on same image ID or you keep separate database tracking on what image id that specific image is on which cloud and zone. After all it is the one identifier that is unique within the deployment you can trust that it's that your specific image."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-09-29 15:25:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Right, this is the use case that I'm worried about, especially with the rise of "Edge Computing". Having a policy that allows deployers to allow some users to upload images and set the ID works for private clouds, but doesn't help consumers of public clouds.'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-04 15:30:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> Right, this is the use case that I'm worried about, especially with the rise of "Edge Computing". Having a policy that allows deployers to allow some users to upload images and set the ID works for private clouds, but doesn't help consumers of public clouds.

@Doug: Maybe this is an education issue?  The 'checksum' field is indexed and an image-list call can be filtered by 'checksum' to locate an image.  Unfortunately, the checksum used is md5 which is no longer collision resistant, but there's a spec proposed [0] to add a stronger hash to images in Queens.  So instead of relying on UUID, the os_hash_value can act as a unique identifier to locate the image.  Would this work for the edge computing use case?

[0] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/507568/'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-05 13:46:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Here are the results of the operators' survey:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-operators/2017-October/014344.html"}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2017-10-05 18:47:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

As far as the Interop WG is concerned, we will flag and remove and capability that is an unfixable security bug. If this warrants narrowing of the guidelines, it's in service of the end users. As an individual member of the WG, I'll support any solution adopted by the Glance team. For the proposed solution, I personally have no strong opinion in any direction or another, aside from trusting Brian's instincts on turning more control over to operators in a rational and well documented way."}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-06 12:33:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We agreed at the weekly glance meeting on 5 Oct 2017 to grant a spec freeze exception to this proposal to allow some more time for discussion.  We are, however, committed to fixing this problem in Queens.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2017-10-09 04:56:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

TBH, I would be more in favor of removing the feature entirely, mostly because I agree with Jay's statements that security is more important.

However, in this case, the feature is also important and, if there's a different solution that could help with keeping the feature, then why not?

I really don't like the idea of an ever growing table and I also don't like the idea of introducing more interoperability "challenges" to Glance's API.

Would it be ok to adopt the database solution as an interim solution until we find a better one? If we create a table/column/you name it and we keep track of the used ids, we can then go ahead and purge it in the future when/if we find a better solution to this problem. Unfortunately, it wouldn't be easy to do the same if we add a policy (or if we remove the feature entirely).

Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-10-09 14:22:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> > Right, this is the use case that I'm worried about, especially
 > with the rise of "Edge Computing". Having a policy that allows
 > deployers to allow some users to upload images and set the ID works
 > for private clouds, but doesn't help consumers of public clouds.
 > 
 > @Doug: Maybe this is an education issue?  The 'checksum' field is
 > indexed and an image-list call can be filtered by 'checksum' to
 > locate an image.  Unfortunately, the checksum used is md5 which is
 > no longer collision resistant, but there's a spec proposed [0] to
 > add a stronger hash to images in Queens.  So instead of relying on
 > UUID, the os_hash_value can act as a unique identifier to locate
 > the image.  Would this work for the edge computing use case?
 > 
 > [0] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/507568/

That might help. Maybe an example in the documentation would help highlight the way that field is expected to be used. And especially in the client and shade documentation.

Can we guarantee that the checksum is the same for a given image uploaded to multiple regions? Nothing about the upload or processing changes the contents, right?'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-14 15:55:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Can we guarantee that the checksum is the same for a given image uploaded to multiple regions? Nothing about the upload or processing changes the contents, right?

That's a good question.  With the interoperable image import process, I don't think we can guarantee this.  Something as simple as ungzipping a file, examining it, and then re-gzipping (suppose the deployer wants to use a particular compression level or something) will result in different checksums in different regions (since gzip includes a timestamp in the file header).

So what an end user could do in this situation would be to create a custom image property, say, 'my_id' and give it some specific value (say, 'abcde') for that particular image.  The image would be created in each region with the property 'my_id': 'abcde', and then the same image data would be imported into each region.  Then to discover that image in any region, an end user would call GET /v2/images?visibility=private&my_id=abcde (or, if looking for a shared or community image, the query should be filtered by owner also).  Assuming that my_id were being maintained correctly (that is, the owner doesn't use the same value for my_id on different images), this query would return exactly one image in the image-list response, and then the end user could grab the image_id in that region to pass to nova or cinder or whatever service is going to use the image.  This approach gives the image owner the burden of maintaining the my_id field, but if the owner uses a uuid4 to populate this field, the owner won't have to worry about incrementing some kind of counter or something.  The owner *will* have to remember the value to populate my_id in each region, but we're already assuming that the owner is remembering a uuid4 to pass in as the value of the image_id under the current scheme, so this is basically the same thing."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2017-10-14 16:12:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> > Can we guarantee that the checksum is the same for a given image
 > uploaded to multiple regions? Nothing about the upload or
 > processing changes the contents, right?
 > 
 > That's a good question.  With the interoperable image import
 > process, I don't think we can guarantee this.  Something as simple
 > as ungzipping a file, examining it, and then re-gzipping (suppose
 > the deployer wants to use a particular compression level or
 > something) will result in different checksums in different regions
 > (since gzip includes a timestamp in the file header).
 > 
 > So what an end user could do in this situation would be to create a
 > custom image property, say, 'my_id' and give it some specific value
 > (say, 'abcde') for that particular image.  The image would be
 > created in each region with the property 'my_id': 'abcde', and then
 > the same image data would be imported into each region.  Then to
 > discover that image in any region, an end user would call GET
 > /v2/images?visibility=private&my_id=abcde (or, if looking for a
 > shared or community image, the query should be filtered by owner
 > also).  Assuming that my_id were being maintained correctly (that
 > is, the owner doesn't use the same value for my_id on different
 > images), this query would return exactly one image in the
 > image-list response, and then the end user could grab the image_id
 > in that region to pass to nova or cinder or whatever service is
 > going to use the image.  This approach gives the image owner the
 > burden of maintaining the my_id field, but if the owner uses a
 > uuid4 to populate this field, the owner won't have to worry about
 > incrementing some kind of counter or something.  The owner *will*
 > have to remember the value to populate my_id in each region, but
 > we're already assuming that the owner is remembering a uuid4 to
 > pass in as the value of the image_id under the current scheme, so
 > this is basically the same thing.

That leaves it up to users to establish a convention. It won't work between clouds, if different communities of users have different conventions for the attribute name.

What are the challenges with building this into the service directly somehow?"}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-14 16:20:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> Would it be ok to adopt the database solution as an interim solution until we find a better one?

I don't think we're going to find a better solution.  The image_id is an opaque identifier, so the only way to know that one has ever been used is to keep a list of used image_ids.  We can make this a "skinny" list by only keeping image_ids that have ever gone into 'active' status, but it's still going to be an unbounded list.  So it's not a sustainable solution, so I don't see the point of implementing it now.

I wasn't around for the initial design decision, but I imagine that uuid4 was chosen as the way to generate image_ids for precisely the reason that you'd never have to worry about an image_id being re-used because the probability of generating a duplicate is so extremely remote.  So if we assign uuid4s, we don't need to keep a table of used image_ids because we can let randomness work for us.

Allowing the image_id to be set breaks this.  It commits us to having to keep a list of used image_ids.  If we restrict this to "responsible" users (e.g., admins), then maybe this is OK because the "responsible" user is taking on the burden of guaranteeing that once an (image_id, checksum) pair exists, that image_id will always map to that checksum.  But as the range of "responsible" users is increased, the likelihood of the OSSN-0075 exploit increases.

So ideally, I'd prefer to eliminate the ability to set an image_id entirely.  But since it has existed since Bexar or so, that could cause a problem for operators.  So I'm willing to compromise by introducing a policy with the default setting of "!" (i.e., no one can do it), and then allow operators to decide if they want to loosen the restriction given OSSN-0075.  But this is something that should not be exposed to end-users.'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-16 17:33:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> That leaves it up to users to establish a convention. It won't work between clouds, if different communities of users have different conventions for the attribute name.

What we could do is introduce a new "common image property", something like 'os_cross_region_id'.  As a common image property, it would be available in any cloud that defines it in schema-image.json (and it would be easy for operators to back-port this; all they'd have to do is adjust schema-image.json).  It would be self-enforcing (if you want users to easily find your image in various regions/clouds, you'd use this).  Also, properties in schema-image.json are legal image properties even if an operator has allow_additional_image_properties = False (which is not the default).

> What are the challenges with building this into the service directly somehow?

This would be easy, we'd just need to agree on a name and add it to schema-image.json (and publicize it so that people know that it's available).  Glance wouldn't do any policing of the value (other than ensuring it's a string) because Glance would have no way of knowing what's supposed to be in there.

If this sounds reasonable, I'll add it to the spec since it would allow a complete replacement for being able to set the image_id, and it will work in all stable branches.'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-16 17:34:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Forgot to add an @Doug to the previous comment.  Also, the common image properties I refer to are documented here: https://docs.openstack.org/glance/latest/user/common-image-properties.html'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-31 14:39:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2017-10-31 14:54:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

This version supplies a more robust solution to the cross-region image discovery problem, which I think is the only legitimate use case for allowing the image_id to be set.  I also point out that there's a data integrity issue with using image_ids for this purpose that's independent of whether or not the database is purged.  Trying to fix this in the database is not going to address the larger issue, so I think we should give up on looking for a database-based solution.

The API-WG, the Interoperability SIG , and those operators who have cared to comment are not bothered by the backward-incompatibility this introduces.  The operators survey indicates that this is not currently a widely used feature.  The spec proposes an alternative method to perform cross-region image discovery that's safer than the current method, so that's what we should be focused on."}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2018-03-05 13:24:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2018-03-05 15:44:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

The cmd2-0.9.0 is python3-only and the tempest venv is built
unconstrained, so it's trying to bring in the latest version
which is incompatible with python2. We pin the library to
ensure that the venv build completes correctly.

Depends-On: I35e3688ae632d5f7747f32dafc41d23883c033c5
Change-Id: Id5b9274ce39dec3d5ee295d7ef941bf42ca7cbd2

(cherry picked from commit 8c7b78424f699f19ea0a11e4c9dfee78cee1976f)
"}]
commit_message:
Pin cmd2 to the last python2 version of the library

The cmd2-0.9.0 is python3-only and the tempest venv is built
unconstrained, so it's trying to bring in the latest version
which is incompatible with python2. We pin the library to
ensure that the venv build completes correctly.

Depends-On: I35e3688ae632d5f7747f32dafc41d23883c033c5
Change-Id: Id5b9274ce39dec3d5ee295d7ef941bf42ca7cbd2
Signed-off-by: Maksim Malchuk <maksim.malchuk@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 8c7b78424f699f19ea0a11e4c9dfee78cee1976f)

commit_message:
Configure tempest [compute-feature-enabled]/nova_network=False

Starting in Rocky, nova is removing the deprecated
nova-network specific APIs and they will return a 410
response on any microversion.

This change configures Tempest to not run tests against
those nova-network specific APIs.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/571556/

Part of nova blueprint remove-nova-network

Change-Id: I7a21eacdb554d1d8339d773dba464eb9cd110e90

commit_message:
Use renamed kolla_action variable

The kolla-cli code was still using the action variable instead of
the new kolla_action variable so actions using the old variable
name were failing.

commit_message:
Add kata-run job to kata-containers/proxy

This is likely to not work yet, but since we aren't gating on
kata-containers/proxy we won't import job config from that repo which
would make these changes self testing. In order to get the ball moving
we need to start somewhere so start here.

This adds a vexxhost specific bionic image which we will start with
until the nodepool azure driver is tested and deployed. We should be
able to make progress on adding jobs and getting the driver going in
parallel this way.

Change-Id: Ia56c2cb3046e31e50014c8bf24342cceacb7db8a

commit_message:
use only exceptions for uri validations

Currently we use asserts for uri validation, which is not good
practice because assert will be deleted from optimized code.
We must use exceptions in such cases.

Co-authored-by: kairat_kushaev <kkushaev@mirantis.com>
Co-authored-by: Brian Rosmaita <rosmaita.fossdev@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I89c5f1b74be89c759d5754d6cab54dc86c946be1

commit_message:
Add --export option to environment-get

Use --export to give output suitable for importing via
environment-update. The other 'get-definition' commands will be
deprecated in favor of a --export option to 'get' and 'show'

Change-Id: I1bf9b621b498b6978d6fa5903db58c1474b31c93
Closes-Bug: #1769491

commit_message:
Remove deprecated ansible driver options

these are ansible_deploy_username and ansible_deploy_key_file.
Operators will have to set ansible_username and ansible_key_file
node drover_info fields instead.

commit_message:
Improve idempotency

These discovery tasks always show up as "changed" in the Ansible
output. This patch ensures that they are not labeled as changed
when they are run.

The patch also fixes the idempotency check grep so that it works
properly with multiple hosts. Previously, if *any* of the hosts
finished with no changes/failures, the entire job was marked as
passing the idempotency tests.

Depends-On: I17748b0dd2307fd9bee705140c67883140090298
Change-Id: Ie414d32d39fdeeedd77fe94b57a09ba344084ec1
Signed-off-by: Major Hayden <major@mhtx.net>
(cherry picked from commit 391a951f70381246bddfa677e08aaad221e086e3)

commit_message:
Don't restart ivs/nfvswitch in os-net-config

Restarting ivs during ugrades causes network disruptions. Removing both
the ivs and nvfswitch restarts as they are not required.

Change-Id: I3d26cbc8484c72d6bfc133c59c8fc065add226c9
Closes-Bug: 1757130
(cherry picked from commit db081a75c5d2b7a99b4b796f9de7a4aadd7ab522)
(cherry picked from commit 08a0f081bf627ef09b934b2cc1dc66e172a1dbd4)

commit_message:
Add validation to avoid the upgrade if the Overcloud stack name has underscores.

We need to ensure the Overcloud is fixed before proceeding with an Upgrade.

Fix only for stable/newton
Resolves: rhbz#1576839
Change-Id: I203d1b4bee19d24e0cadd52d66556f3e6af68528
Closes-Bug: 1775404

commit_message:
NetApp ONTAP: Fix export path used as volume name

On ONTAP NFS driver, the export path was being used as the volume
name. If the export path is different than the volume name, the
API call to delete files would fail and the driver would invoke
a fallback method that deletes the files manually. This patch fixes
that by finding the correct volume name.

(cherry-picked from commit dbca62c207d63bbc192acf75ae39c6b56702295a)
Change-Id: Ice78889573a36ff5e8873a0d316ddcf180d0263f
Closes-bug: #1690954

commit_message:
Adds check and resyncs ODL/OVS OF pipeline

Some flows may be missing in OVS (on a per table basis) when deploying
with OpenDaylight. There is no OpenDaylight fix yet for this issue, so
this patch implements a workaround. The workaround is to check if all
the tables exist on each OVS node. If they are missing, then reset the
OpenFlow connection to the ODL controller, which will result in ODL
pushing the flows again and inserting the missing flows.

Closes-Bug: 1775436

Change-Id: I28d13a26198268cfd1f3e9e64236605f24319a04
Signed-off-by: Tim Rozet <trozet@redhat.com>

What's the reason for the revert?"}, {'account_id': 9712, 'date': '2018-06-04 15:35:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I discussed this with a bunch of people. There are two reasons.

- There is a desire to backport this, but a new CLI command is a feature. Backporting that is a non-starter IMO.
- We could have came up with a more elegant approach to solving this. A new CLI command wasn't really needed, I actually mentioned this on the original review and shouldn't have added a +2. I am going to propose that we add "--export" to the mistral environment-get command, that will format the output in a way it can be used by environment-update. Then we simply add a new flag to an existing command.'}, {'account_id': 15895, 'date': '2018-06-05 10:28:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 15895, 'date': '2018-06-05 10:28:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 15895, 'date': '2018-06-05 10:29:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I understand the backport issue but I don't see how this is any different than the workflow-get-definition and workbook-get-definition commands.  I think it's consistent to have environment-get-definition.

I have no problem with --export but I think for consistency it should be added to the workflow-get and workbook-get commands."}, {'account_id': 9712, 'date': '2018-06-06 14:08:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 7065, 'date': '2018-06-06 14:29:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Switch to specific flavor and slowly bump capacity

We've got new capacity to donate to the OpenStack infrastructure,
this also includes a flavor that includes disk by default to avoid
any issues with boot-from-volume.

We'll be bumping this number up soon but just wanted to test things
out and make sure nothing crash-and-burns.

Change-Id: I60f288cda65b808c2612beb1efb03919c075de98

commit_message:
Hide old images from default image-list

The spec looks how operators can have more control over images
that are included in the default image list. This is achieved
with a new property 'hidden' to omit images from the users.

Change-Id: I7bba164c350e74f9d3490c77d536bffdc1ccc075

[{'created': '2018-06-06 13:56:18.000000000', 'message': 'Fix: Router port always marked as DOWN

Router ports in OVN is never bound to a host given their decentralized
nature. For that reason, the code in Neutron core that change the status
of the ports (router ports are normal ports underneath) was ignoring the
OVN router ports.

This patch is forcing the status of those router ports to ACTIVE in
networking-ovn. A comment was left in the code in case we want to change
the core Neutron approach in the future.

This patch is also enabling two tempest tests that checks for this
router port status which were disabled before.

Change-Id: I5fd18e6e395a783e9591c058b80b63d42b24a3df
Closes-Bug: #1715126
'}]
commit_message:
Fix: Router port always marked as DOWN

Router ports in OVN is never bound to a host given their decentralized
nature. For that reason, the code in Neutron core that change the status
of the ports (router ports are normal ports underneath) was ignoring the
OVN router ports.

This patch is forcing the status of those router ports to ACTIVE in
networking-ovn. A comment was left in the code in case we want to change
the core Neutron approach in the future.

This patch is also enabling two tempest tests that checks for this
router port status which were disabled before.

Change-Id: I5fd18e6e395a783e9591c058b80b63d42b24a3df
Closes-Bug: #1715126

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not

breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I03574b12fc9ef07ce459e81c9b8219a3b10bd4da
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

subject: (airship) Disable verify permission for CI
messages:
[{'account_id': 26449, 'date': '2018-06-07 16:33:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2018-06-07 16:34:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Can you explain the motivation behind this change? Code-Review is expected to be review done by humans and this breaks that expectation.'}, {'account_id': 26365, 'date': '2018-06-07 16:34:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2018-06-07 16:50:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I agree with clark - I'd like to understand the motivation.

The overall model we tend to use is that Zuul has Verified +/- 2 (and is the only one that has that) that third-party CI has Verified +/- 1 (which indicates that a computer has done verification tasks, but that computer is informative and not binding)

When we roll out gerrit 2.15 there is a specific new data structure that will be for 3rd-party CI's registering their votes so we can display them as an understandable matrix/table.

Anyway - what are you looking to accomplish/solve? I'd love to understand the issue more."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2018-06-07 16:52:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 26449, 'date': '2018-06-07 17:33:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> I agree with clark - I'd like to understand the motivation.
 > 
 > The overall model we tend to use is that Zuul has Verified +/- 2
 > (and is the only one that has that) that third-party CI has
 > Verified +/- 1 (which indicates that a computer has done
 > verification tasks, but that computer is informative and not
 > binding)
 > 
 > When we roll out gerrit 2.15 there is a specific new data structure
 > that will be for 3rd-party CI's registering their votes so we can
 > display them as an understandable matrix/table.
 > 
 > Anyway - what are you looking to accomplish/solve? I'd love to
 > understand the issue more.

Our 3rd party gates are broken and I was directed by our CICD team it was our mistake to enable them to vote on the Verify label and block the merge of PS by Zuul. So this patchset is an attempt to correct that. I'm new to project config stuff, so this may be the wrong avenue to correct this issue. The target state (for now, until our 3rd party gates are fixed) is to allow them to vote CR +/-1 so reviewers can see the results, but it doesn't block Zuul's gate pipeline."}, {'account_id': 26449, 'date': '2018-06-07 17:35:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> > I agree with clark - I'd like to understand the motivation.
 > >
 > > The overall model we tend to use is that Zuul has Verified +/- 2
 > > (and is the only one that has that) that third-party CI has
 > > Verified +/- 1 (which indicates that a computer has done
 > > verification tasks, but that computer is informative and not
 > > binding)
 > >
 > > When we roll out gerrit 2.15 there is a specific new data
 > structure
 > > that will be for 3rd-party CI's registering their votes so we can
 > > display them as an understandable matrix/table.
 > >
 > > Anyway - what are you looking to accomplish/solve? I'd love to
 > > understand the issue more.
 > 
 > Our 3rd party gates are broken and I was directed by our CICD team
 > it was our mistake to enable them to vote on the Verify label and
 > block the merge of PS by Zuul. So this patchset is an attempt to
 > correct that. I'm new to project config stuff, so this may be the
 > wrong avenue to correct this issue. The target state (for now,
 > until our 3rd party gates are fixed) is to allow them to vote CR
 > +/-1 so reviewers can see the results, but it doesn't block Zuul's
 > gate pipeline.

I should correct the above to say target state is allowing them to vote in some way that indicates results, but is not gating. Code-Review may not be the correct label for that."}, {'account_id': 26449, 'date': '2018-06-07 17:48:59.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Thanks to Clark's advice, I'll abandon this PS with the plan to remove our CICD robot account from airship-ci."}]

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I6c11da63a69121680db525ffdd350cfdde89b1f8
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Namespace deletion functionality for namespace_subnet driver

This patch extends the namespace_subnet driver to handle namespace
deletion. It ensures the created resources during namespace creation
are removed upon namespace deletion.

Note it does not currently support deleting the extra ports created
by the ports pool feature, so it should not be used if ports pool
feature is enabled. A follow up patch will address this issue

Partially Implements: blueprint network-namespace

Change-Id: I2eed278dafacd5090a902bacfd366f7cdf9edca4

commit_message:
Add afsmon project

This is an import of some code I developed for proof-of concept to
send AFS statistic to statsd.  It is currently working in a manual
fashion (see some details on the stats in
I8066f05df0c8eb2f4e211beaa25bccbd0261ca9b) so I think this fits best
in openstack-infra before it gets puppeted for automatic deployment.

Needed-By: https://review.openstack.org/572527
Change-Id: Ie7c491acf4ff734964be73487dc230478adfa96f

The role is functional and it can install a cluster succesfully

commit_message:
Remove the deprecated config option

The option 'allow_inuse_volume_type_modification' is
introduced as a bridge to not break upgrades without
notice. It is introduced in Ocata release [1], so it
is time to remove this option.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/440680/

Change-Id: I8c61b11994c1f8f571e65cefe4965f7d69b13100

commit_message:
Add note to dev_setup doc

1.Add note(PIP_UPGRADE) for local.conf.
2.Move bash to code-block: console. If not, the quotation marks
will display as Chinese character.

Change-Id: I48f899de345b8dc85b992d18b10922db5fa107e1

[{'created': '2018-06-07 11:39:48.000000000', 'message': 'Fix sphinx-docs job for stable branch

build-openstack-sphinx-docs jobs fail on stable branches due to the new
pip version 10 introduces some previously Warning as Error: in case of
calling "pip install" without any package name, the command fails.
tox_install.sh is called during docs job without any package passed to
pip.

On master and stable/queens tox_install.sh is not used anymore, this is
why stable/pike is the first version to be fixed.

Change-Id: Ic714e919542bd64194ba0d73910508d335719b68
'}]
commit_message:
Fix sphinx-docs job for stable branch

build-openstack-sphinx-docs jobs fail on stable branches due to the new
pip version 10 introduces some previously Warning as Error: in case of
calling "pip install" without any package name, the command fails.
tox_install.sh is called during docs job without any package passed to
pip.

On master and stable/queens tox_install.sh is not used anymore, this is
why stable/pike is the first version to be fixed.

Change-Id: Ic714e919542bd64194ba0d73910508d335719b68

[{'created': '2018-06-02 19:12:17.000000000', 'message': "Convert puppet-openstackci jobs to zuulv3

This patch moves the puppet-openstackci beaker jobs out of legacy. Since
this job is essentially the same as the regular beaker jobs, we don't
need new playbooks, we just need to adjust the beaker-rspec playbooks to
run the puppet-openstackci tests.

Since this was the last legacy job in the infra-puppet-apply-jobs
template, move it out of the legacy templates to the regular templates.

commit_message:
Convert puppet-openstackci jobs to zuulv3

This patch moves the puppet-openstackci beaker jobs out of legacy. Since
this job is essentially the same as the regular beaker jobs, we don't
need new playbooks, we just need to adjust the beaker-rspec playbooks to
run the puppet-openstackci tests.

Since this was the last legacy job in the infra-puppet-apply-jobs
template, move it out of the legacy templates to the regular templates.

This doesn't remove the legacy-puppet-openstackci-beaker-rspec jobs
or their parent legacy-openstackci-base since those are still defined in
project-config.

Change-Id: I7f7cb133fc41eba07da224291b7f2d0659b0deb6

commit_message:
Fix sphinx-docs job for stable branch

build-openstack-sphinx-docs jobs fail on stable branches due to the new
pip version 10 introduces some previously Warning as Error: in case of
calling "pip install" without any package name, the command fails.
tox_install.sh is called during docs job without any package passed to
pip.

On master and stable/queens tox_install.sh is not used anymore, this is
why stable/pike is the first version to be fixed.

Change-Id: I8155fb720c35086ed3719fd282b8944627129f14

commit_message:
Convert infra's beaker jobs for zuulv3

This patch moves the legacy beaker jobs that were being used for Infra's
puppet modules out of the legecy definitions and into the regular list.

Historically, the test scripts were shared between the Infra and Puppet
OpenStack teams, but the Puppet OpenStack team has already moved their
jobs in-repo so we can remove tasks specific to their setup.

We need to leave some jobs and playbooks in place that are still being
used by the puppet-midonet project which belongs to neither team.

Change-Id: Iefea6ee173cff2bf050d99d96ae2e1d1a51b7f49

commit_message:
Pass currentPlanName when fetching available roles

fetchAvailableRoles did not get planName argument passed in, so
available roles were always listed from 'overcloud' deployment
plan

Task: 20022
Story: 2002168
Change-Id: I7fdaa4031d5e093f88c31201ae8ca261469f57a6
(cherry picked from commit 983ec321dcbcca21f98a5b5360af159813de6bef)

commit_message:
Update the version of erlang to support rabbitmq

The version of erlang we're using, while functional, is not recommended.
This change updates our version of erlang for rabbitmq to be the
recommended version by changing the pinned version of erlang.

The apt package pinning meta dependency has been removed and put into
the apt task file as an include role. To ensure a more uniform process
for setting the version of erlang used with rabbitmq the new variable
`rabbitmq_erlang_version_spec` has been added. This option has a default
of "null" and is set by distro specific variables when applicable.

Erlang version support matrix: https://www.rabbitmq.com/which-erlang.html

Change-Id: Iced12d4533eec068bd11d8bd235d81308ef40427
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I3edccb24a3f714be8fcc32851342363e44f7ea2f
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Stop installing percona-release and setup using yum_repository

Due to the security role adding the `localpkg_gpgcheck` option and
the fact that the Percona release RPM is not signed, it fails to
install leading to failing gate for CentOS.

The behaviour for Debian-based operating systems is to manually
install the repositories so let's switch CentOS to do the same.

Change-Id: I71840bd209cd398e0ce46d61ac895dea68ba193c
Related-Bug: #1675918

commit_message:
Handle Null check for STD_ATTR_MAP:

e.g. when running individual UTs, STD_ATTR_MAP fails with keyerror

python -m testtools.run networking_ovn.tests.unit.test_ovn_db_sync.TestOvnSbSyncML2.test_ovn_sb_sync
module = __import__(module_name)
File "networking_ovn/tests/unit/test_ovn_db_sync.py", line 18, in <module>
from networking_ovn.common import ovn_client
File "networking_ovn/common/ovn_client.py", line 41, in <module>
from networking_ovn.db import revision as db_rev
File "networking_ovn/db/revision.py", line 33, in <module>
STD_ATTR_MAP[ovn_const.TYPE_ROUTER_PORTS] = STD_ATTR_MAP[ovn_const.TYPE_PORTS]
KeyError: 'ports'

Hence, this commit fixes the same.

Change-Id: Ie117b69f21c6b247fa52915a8d10902ced634bb5

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I7c221de42f30e6ef52f32b5ccd0905859d027c07
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
devstack: fix octavia allocation ranges

According to the documentation, we should reserve the latter half of the
service subnet cidr so that we don't let octavia vrrp allocate IPs that
can be used by Kubernetes/OpenShift own service IPAM

Closes-Bug: #1763278
Change-Id: Ib4d176ba92cb42cdd6f8105e15843c7e967175cf
Signed-off-by: Antoni Segura Puimedon <antonisp@celebdor.com>

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I370e66f1a4f4a0af629afa109d51d095a4700327
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
tell flake8 to ignore unicode

There is no builtin type 'unicode' under python 3. The code is already
doing the correct thing at runtime, but that check is not evaluated
when the linter runs under python 3 so it fails because the name is
not defined. This change tells the linter to ignore the line in the
exceptions package.

Change-Id: Idea04659d3699ab2243f6c325d13d43abe9b447a
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

[{'created': '2018-06-04 09:39:44.000000000', 'message': "Remove direct tagging/branching for yaql

The release process for official OpenStack components now uses
release requests using changes proposed to the openstack/releases
git repository. This allows peer review of release requests,
including version numbers, and run a series of checks to make
sure the release is likely to be successful once the tag is
pushed. The same process supports the creation of additional repo
branches as well. This all ensures that releases are reported
correctly on the releases.openstack.org website.

As a result of this process, nobody needs to push tags directly
or create branches directly. The yaql library is associated with
the Murano team, which follows that process already. Let's fix the

"}]
commit_message:
Remove direct tagging/branching for yaql

The release process for official OpenStack components now uses
release requests using changes proposed to the openstack/releases
git repository. This allows peer review of release requests,
including version numbers, and run a series of checks to make
sure the release is likely to be successful once the tag is
pushed. The same process supports the creation of additional repo
branches as well. This all ensures that releases are reported
correctly on the releases.openstack.org website.

As a result of this process, nobody needs to push tags directly
or create branches directly. The yaql library is associated with
the Murano team, which follows that process already. Let's fix the
ACLs to remove direct tagging/branching for yaql as well.

Change-Id: I98f438ebfa521bd59e3f607e99d73e2ab0777b91

commit_message:
vars: Do not pull devel packages on distro installations

The devel packages are only needed to build the pip pacakges so we don't
need them when we install packages straight from the distro repos.

Change-Id: Ie598d5c4e9319867793ac34ef62f5d7c11d082fd
Implements: blueprint openstack-distribution-packages

commit_message:
Fix build error due to doc warning and l-c

Warning generated due to title line being too short. With warnings
now being treated as errors, this causes docs builds to fail.

Lower-constraints also out of sync with actual versions used in
requirements files causing requirements validation errors too.

Due to Zuul job changes, need both changes together to get things
to pass.

Change-Id: I769c679389cb0985b53561105c5244637502b226

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: Id88b2b77ae225a88238331ca245a0fc90a742039
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: If3aad2663d76fce58430d3b6ee6220ff550977a3
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
K8s datasource configuration doc

 this document describes how to config kubernetes datasource:

   * copy kubernetes cluster config file

@Lingxian Kong, OK.'}, {'account_id': 21781, 'date': '2018-06-05 10:39:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

> Besides, I have found that host will create cgroup files for each
 > pod like '/sys/fs/cgroup/memory(cpu)/kubepods/besteffort(qosClass)/pod<uid>/<containerID>/',
 > under the above path we can see the tasks file, in which will
 > include all the pids running in the container. So we may not need
 > to create extra cgroup files for function any more.

While I was doing some tests on this, I found unfortunately this was not always true with docker using different cgroup drivers. On CentOS 7 I use systemd as cgroup driver for docker ("dockerd --exec-opt native.cgroupdriver=systemd") and the paths are obviously different. See [1] for some reference. I cannot recall why I change to the systemd cgroupdriver and made it the default when we deploy qinling on CentOS 7 [2]. I will try to use the cgroupfs driver and see what will happen.

[1] https://github.com/kubernetes-incubator/cri-o/issues/842
[2] I6fe3c3445844597bfd1b603c1a97687d550f5e87'}, {'account_id': 21781, 'date': '2018-06-05 10:53:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

> I cannot recall
 > why I change to the systemd cgroupdriver and made it the default
 > when we deploy qinling on CentOS 7.

When installing kubeadm on CentOS 7, it changes the kubelet's cgroup driver to systemd, so docker should use the same one. I guess both can be changed to cgroupfs."}, {'account_id': 21781, 'date': '2018-06-05 11:23:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Published edit on patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 21781, 'date': '2018-06-05 11:24:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Added a debug message showing workers info'}, {'account_id': 21781, 'date': '2018-06-05 12:58:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

I've found the cause of the tempest failure "Failed to get current worker information". It happens when two or more executions are concurrently created and the function is scaled up. When the first one is created, the function is not yet scaled up and then the second is created, one more worker is created and that worker is then chosen by k8s to run the first execution. The workers info in the first request doesn't contain the new worker's info and leads to the failure.

With the following one-liner it is reproducible:
for i in `seq 9`; do  openstack function execution create  <FUNCTION_ID>  --async &  done

Let's try to fix this concurrency problem.'}, {'account_id': 27695, 'date': '2018-06-05 13:14:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

commit_message:
Runtime implementation for non-image type function.

Using 'cgroup' in runtime server to limit cpu and memory resources.

Each pod in deployment will has respective 'cgroup' directory on host.
Under '/sys/fs/cgroup/xx/kubepods/<qos_class>/pod<uid>' directory, use
HOSTNAME to create a new cgroup folder, which will only be used to
limit function execution. Then we do not need to care about how and
when to delete this new folder on host.

Use 'openstackqinling/python-runtime:0.0.3' as the new python runtime
image.

Story: 2001586
Task: 14415
Change-Id: Id04a72c4f4a3c559dc7c746688b13ef93656d125

commit_message:
devstack: use cgroupfs driver for both docker and k8s on Cent OS

This is required for resource limiting for non-image functions as we use
the cgroup paths setup by the cgroupfs driver.

Change-Id: I91c50d5ee70a5973f720fd13c6c6214c7361fb7a

commit_message:
Allow Kolla Ceph to deploy bluestore OSDs in Kolla

Support Kolla Ceph to deploy blustore OSDs. With the patch, Kolla
Ceph can deploy bluestore OSDs on ONE, TWO or THREE storage
devices.

Before deploy bluestore OSD, please prepare devices. The detailed
Please refer to [1] for devices initialization.

extend_start.sh: initialize and start bluestore OSD

find_disk.py: search the devices for bluestore OSD

[1]: specs/kolla-ceph-bluestore.rst

Partially-Implements: blueprint kolla-ceph-bluestore

Change-Id: I832f490de63e1aeb68814697cda610a51b622c1f
Signed-off-by: Tone Zhang <tone.zhang@arm.com>

commit_message:
Switch containerized job to Octavia

As our default LB choice is Octavia, this commit moves containerized
LBaaS v2 job to exeprimental queue and promotes containerized Octavia
job to check and gate queues.

Change-Id: Idb1a8b4b17dd9b13f63c1b01f9291e7f02d1663e

Remove Cinder API v1 compatibility

Since Cinder API v1 is removed in I03bf2db5bd7e2fdfb4f6032758ccaf2b348a82ba
we don't need _replace_v2_parameters function anymore.

commit_message:
Redirect the old baremetal install-guide for master to its current location

People seem to find /project-install-guide/baremetal/draft pretty often,
and assume that it's the up-to-date installation docs for ironic, while
in reality it is frozen at some point around Pike. Let us redirect
to the actual master installation docs.

Change-Id: I32b5fc3e0d6e18c5804b80b8bc2d6d976a689ba8

commit_message:
osprofiler support redis

Currently osprofiler only choose elasticsearch,
which is only supported on x86.
On other platform like aarch64 osprofiler can
not be used since no elasticsearch package.

Enable osprofiler by enable_osprofiler: "yes",
which choose elasticsearch by default.
Choose redis by enable_redis: "yes" & osprofiler_backend: "redis"
On platform without elasticsearch support like aarch64
set enable_elasticsearch: "no"

Change-Id: I68fe7a33e11d28684962fc5d0b3d326e90784d78

snmp: ignore rfc1905.NoSuchInstance result

If the SNMP polling return such a value, it should be ignored.

(cherry picked from commit 93eca81e588465da9900202b32bdcd8ddad0d866)

I agree we should have check/gate CI, and there is already experimental coverage via scenario 009 which Flavio added a while ago.

[{'created': '2018-05-15 14:45:53.000000000', 'message': 'Decouple OpenShiftGlusterDisks from openshift-master.yaml

In the event you have different disks in nodes assigned to each role
you may need to pass role specific parameters, e.g like:

parameter_defaults:
  OpenShiftMasterParameters:
    OpenShiftGlusterDisks:
      - /dev/vdc
  OpenShiftWorkerParameters:

commit_message:
Decouple OpenShiftGlusterDisks from openshift-master.yaml

In the event you have different disks in nodes assigned to each role
you may need to pass role specific parameters, e.g like:

parameter_defaults:
  OpenShiftMasterParameters:
    OpenShiftGlusterDisks:
      - /dev/vdc
  OpenShiftWorkerParameters:
    OpenShiftGlusterDisks:
      - /dev/vdd

To enable that we create an inventory file per role, and pass the directory
of files to ansible.

Change-Id: I8b4d8698405ffb004b081e1f097f300216edfa77

commit_message:
Add setup script for kolla-cli / kolla-ansible

Created new cli-setup.py script that automates the previously
manual process to create the directories needed for the kolla-cli
and kolla-ansible.  It also improves on the process by leaving the
globals.yml file in place in /etc/kolla and just creating a link
to the group_vars/__GLOBALS__ so that both the kolla-ansible and
kolla-cli commands will work correctly, rather than having their
functioning being mutually exclusive.  Due to kolla-ansible still
expecting to be run as root for most actions the cli_setup.py
script should also be run via sudo.

Change-Id: I5b59317b2c22d10dd82623a548b64f387b6bc9d3

commit_message:
Add a new tempest job with a mock datasource

In this tempest job, the mock datasource is used to create an entity
graph with ~20,000 vertices. This job will contain tests for
init procedure, processes, restarts, multiple api calls.

Other data sources are disabled. Heat, Telemetry, Mistral
are not installed.

This commit includes the first two tests, both using a template where
each action causes another action (three levels).
one test restarts vitrage-graph so the init procedure evaluates this template.
the other test does not restart. result should be the same.

Change-Id: I9c4c329983bbe5930de5484fa6932b318746ed5c

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I6b107fce3daa8292b5fe6b5730a03008bf8987f0
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I9a8f7b1734b23751e47297a15676219627969d7c
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Using oslo.policy for monasca-api

Added policies and used policy enforcement engine
from monasca-common.

- Replaced security with oslo.policy
- Updated unit tests and implemented some new tests
- Added a new entry point for generating sample policy file by tox

task: 6355

commit_message:
Pin cmd2 to the last python2 version of the library

The cmd2-0.9.0 is python3-only and the tempest venv is built
unconstrained, so it's trying to bring in the latest version
which is incompatible with python2. We pin the library to
ensure that the venv build completes correctly.

Depends-On: I35e3688ae632d5f7747f32dafc41d23883c033c5
Change-Id: Id5b9274ce39dec3d5ee295d7ef941bf42ca7cbd2
Signed-off-by: Maksim Malchuk <maksim.malchuk@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 8c7b78424f699f19ea0a11e4c9dfee78cee1976f)

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Decode subprocess output so it has the right type under python 3.

Change-Id: Id2df5439fa6e788199bec4ac7c98c56347053621
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Refactor exception handling in cmd.api

Replace the known exception tuple with a map of exception classes
to error codes to preserve backward compatibility of exit codes.
Also change the code to handle unknown members of the Exception
hierarchy without breaking.

Co-authored-by: jiangpch <jiangpengcheng@navercorp.com>
Co-authored-by: Brian Rosmaita <rosmaita.fossdev@gmail.com>

Closes-Bug: #1726213

Change-Id: Iabfc2ded45a576a18bdb30a6c3ada8b9799a3196

commit_message:
Updating time for functional tests

Currenlty, some gates is being failed with logs like this

"""
b'Response: {"description": "Provided object does not match schema
\'Secret\': \'expiration\' is before current time.
Invalid property: \'expiration\'", "title": "Bad Request", "code": 400}'
"""

So it is necessary to update the time to create secrets successfully.

Change-Id: I4f2d3817d9a2380919d16e76ef5dcba3ec62e5a1

commit_message:
tox: Switch basepython to 3

Python 3 is coming. Switch everything that isn't explicitly targeted to
a specific version to Python 3, allowing us to validate what will soon
be the primary target.

Change-Id: Ic4187023b9163d4c145d7c5061c0af9ee3ff97be

subject: Dockerfile to run unit tests
revisions:
[{'created': '2018-05-29 08:59:41.000000000', 'message': 'Dockerfile to run unit tests

Docker containers are very useful for developers because they are
lighter than VMs and permits to have snapshots of each image, allowing
the developer to quickly check changes between different commits and to
have a clean environment to test their changes. Also, they can be used
in the CI system, freeing up resources.

This Dockerfile permits to create a container with all the requirements
needed to run the unit tests, you have to follow the next steps (ipv6 has to
be enabled in your docker daemon [1]):

1. Build the docker image to run your unit tests (it only depends on the
test-requirements.txt file):

    docker build -t neutron-dev:23sdf .

2. Run your container to set up your test environment mounting your
local folder so you can have access to the artifacts outside of the
container:

docker run -itv $(pwd):/neutron --privileged --sysctl \
    net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6=0  neutron:23sdf bash

3. Run the unit tests inside the container:

cd /neutron
tox -e py27

[1] https://docs.docker.com/config/daemon/ipv6/

Related-Bug: #1773818

Change-Id: I5973c8772d3ca530f9e30710759425adc18994d2
Signed-off-by: aojeagarcia <aojeagarcia@suse.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Dockerfile to run unit tests

Docker containers are very useful for developers because they are
lighter than VMs and permits to have snapshots of each image, allowing
the developer to quickly check changes between different commits and to
have a clean environment to test their changes. Also, they can be used
in the CI system, freeing up resources.

This Dockerfile permits to create a container with all the requirements
needed to run the unit tests, you have to follow the next steps (ipv6 has to
be enabled in your docker daemon [1]):

1. Build the docker image to run your unit tests (it only depends on the
test-requirements.txt file):

    docker build -t neutron-dev:23sdf .

2. Run your container to set up your test environment mounting your
local folder so you can have access to the artifacts outside of the
container:

docker run -itv $(pwd):/neutron --privileged --sysctl \
    net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6=0  neutron:23sdf bash

3. Run the unit tests inside the container:

cd /neutron
tox -e py27

[1] https://docs.docker.com/config/daemon/ipv6/

Related-Bug: #1773818

Change-Id: I5973c8772d3ca530f9e30710759425adc18994d2
Signed-off-by: aojeagarcia <aojeagarcia@suse.com>

Ok. So, some of my concerns with this approach:

1. I need to be able to launch and customize each microservice all on its own. I would like to run them as individual helm instances on my system so that one microservice update can't affect any other. So, 0% orchestration by helm at the services level. This arrangement does not support that. While https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/issues/1568#issuecomment-262086504 shows an approach on how a client based plugin mechanism might work, but that can also be done in the helm chart itself as prototyped in my helm chart poc. I'd rather the templating system do it then the client. But I'm kind of shying away from either approach. Individual packages are the most clean, clear and safe (orchestration free). They will better map "helm upgrade <packagename>" at the microservice level so advanced tooling built on top of helm should support microservice level packages better. (some day "helm upgrade all" for z stream updates)

2. Management overhead. This approach requires dozens of files (after all services converted) to be touched to update a version number. Chart.yaml and values.yaml can not be templated in helm, but for our project, templating them would be very important to not have so much management overhead. We only have so much help. I believe we need to template them all, which requires a build step other then 'helm package'. Once we accept we need to do that, then other things, like filesystem layout are no longer dependent on what helm package requires. So we can make a kolla-kubernetes/templates/<servicename>/<microservicename>.yaml and compile them into their respective packages rather then be restricted to what helm must have for a layout. Ideally, I would want to build a new package for every microservice for every z stream container update I do. This really would require templating or operators will suffer. Again, this would enable the "helm upgrade all" for z stream update use case)

3. Globals seem to me, an unplesent way to expose primary configuration of a package. The var names are already unique enough, the names are long to begin with without needing the prefix, and its unclear how you even specify the globals. I'd guess like:
helm install foo --set global.docker_registry=localhost:4000,global.docker_namespace=region1,global.kolla_base_distro=ubuntu,kolla_install_type=binary
? (with a dot?) ....
#the globals really add up fast.
It also suffers the inability to override at a microservice level. If you 'helm install nova' you can't override the settings on nova-novncproxy without overriding the settings on every other microservice. This lessened flexibility will cause operators problems. It will have even more problems when you make 3 level packages such as openstack->nova->nova-api. globals there leak across everywhere. They aren't quite scoped right for the use case I think.

To me, the most important thing is getting the package granularity right, and the variable api defined, as we will have to support the api for a the long haul. The machinery for building the packages to provide a clean package api, can be ugly for now, until helm gains better machinery of its own.

So, lets come up with a design that:
1. has clean vars api contract that we can support for a long time.
2. modular from a microservice package to a wrapping service package, to a wrapping whole openstack package.
3. templated for ease of maintenance/quick releases by us&operators.
4. maximizes code reuse/minimizes copy&paste coding.'}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-11-28 19:13:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

> Ok. So, some of my concerns with this approach:
> 
> 1. I need to be able to launch and customize each microservice all
> on its own. I would like to run them as individual helm instances
> on my system so that one microservice update can't affect any
> other. So, 0% orchestration by helm at the services level. This
> arrangement does not support that. While https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/issues/1568#issuecomment-262086504
> shows an approach on how a client based plugin mechanism might
> work, but that can also be done in the helm chart itself as
> prototyped in my helm chart poc. I'd rather the templating system
> do it then the client. But I'm kind of shying away from either
> approach. Individual packages are the most clean, clear and safe
> (orchestration free). They will better map "helm upgrade
> <packagename>" at the microservice level so advanced tooling built
> on top of helm should support microservice level packages better.
> (some day "helm upgrade all" for z stream updates)
> 
I think you raise some good points here, though I think the solution suggested in https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/issues/1568#issuecomment-262394195, may work provide rather than excluding packages we specific which subpackage we actually want to install.
If we could do 'helm upgrade OpenStack --subpackage="swift/proxy"' would that alivate your concerns?

> 2. Management overhead. This approach requires dozens of files
> (after all services converted) to be touched to update a version
> number. Chart.yaml and values.yaml can not be templated in helm,
> but for our project, templating them would be very important to not
> have so much management overhead. We only have so much help. I
> believe we need to template them all, which requires a build step
> other then 'helm package'. Once we accept we need to do that, then
> other things, like filesystem layout are no longer dependent on
> what helm package requires. So we can make a kolla-kubernetes/templates/<servicename>/<microservicename>.yaml
> and compile them into their respective packages rather then be
> restricted to what helm must have for a layout. Ideally, I would
> want to build a new package for every microservice for every z
> stream container update I do. This really would require templating
> or operators will suffer. Again, this would enable the "helm
> upgrade all" for z stream update use case)

I both agree and disagree with you here :) As helm stands I think that we will inevitably need to introduce some sort of templating system to process the values.yaml, and version numbering. However I think it would be counterproductive to move away from the standard helm chart layout.
I believe that any templating we do should be as minimal as possible, and should just prepare the tree to the point where a (or several) 'helm package' is possible, as this will reduce the burden on us to produce tooling, provide a lower barrier of entry to users to the project, and hopefully allow us to retire any such feature as helm matures.

> 3. Globals seem to me, an unplesent way to expose primary
> configuration of a package. The var names are already unique
> enough, the names are long to begin with without needing the
> prefix, and its unclear how you even specify the globals. I'd guess
> like:
> helm install foo --set global.docker_registry=localhost:4000,global.docker_namespace=region1,global.kolla_base_distro=ubuntu,kolla_install_type=binary
> ? (with a dot?) ....
> #the globals really add up fast.

The example you have above is indeed pretty horrible - and why I think we will end up wrapping helm for real deployments. 

> It also suffers the inability to override at a microservice level.
> If you 'helm install nova' you can't override the settings on
> nova-novncproxy without overriding the settings on every other
> microservice. This lessened flexibility will cause operators
> problems. It will have even more problems when you make 3 level
> packages such as openstack->nova->nova-api. globals there leak
> across everywhere. They aren't quite scoped right for the use case
> I think.
This is somthing we will need to review - I've thought of a potenital solution, but I'm not sure (using nova as an example):
We include config generation at the service level package or a nova/config subpackage, so users who run 'helm install nova' would get an opinionated deployment with sane defaults. Microservice/sub-packages would not include any confiuration allowing us full controll.
 
> To me, the most important thing is getting the package granularity
> right, and the variable api defined, as we will have to support the
> api for a the long haul. The machinery for building the packages to
> provide a clean package api, can be ugly for now, until helm gains
> better machinery of its own.
It's for this reason I'm heavily in favor of adopting a model that tracks the 'helm' way of doing things as closley as possible - as though the code may not be so elegant initially it stands a better chance of long term survivability without creating out own rabbit warren.

> So, lets come up with a design that:
> 1. has clean vars api contract that we can support for a long time.
> 2. modular from a microservice package to a wrapping service
> package, to a wrapping whole openstack package.
> 3. templated for ease of maintenance/quick releases by
> us&operators.
> 4. maximizes code reuse/minimizes copy&paste coding.
These are the goals we should work towards for sure. :)'}, {'account_id': 23928, 'date': '2016-11-28 19:22:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:
