Ok. So, some of my concerns with this approach:

1. I need to be able to launch and customize each microservice all on its own. I would like to run them as individual helm instances on my system so that one microservice update can't affect any other. So, 0% orchestration by helm at the services level. This arrangement does not support that. 
[SB] Only now, with helm 2.1 introduced, we can render at each level, global kolla-kubernetes, or service or microservice.
[KF] I mention they why I have issue with helm 2.1 below. I want a package for microservice, not a package that you can select a microservice from at instantiate time. Its much easier to trust an update when you know it doesn't contain updates for things not needing to be updated.

While https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/issues/1568#issuecomment-262086504 shows an approach on how a client based plugin mechanism might work, but that can also be done in the helm chart itself as prototyped in my helm chart poc. 

[SB] you approach introduces another level of packaging/building system, which is not the right direction imho, as instead of inventing new tools we need to leverage the ones we already selected. Also that building system is not straight forward with files all over the places and only God and you know how they will be merged together.
[KF] The particular layout I don't particularly care about. I just picked one. If there is a better one, we can figure it out. I assert the premise of building packages though is important, not where exactly the parts come from. The rest, we document as to why, and where it goes.
 
I'd rather the templating system do it then the client. 

[SB] WHy then we use helm, just to package? We should have stayed with jinja2 then if helm is used just to package and you introduce another templating engine on top.
[KF] Because there are two templating issues here, not just one. Helm solves the issue of templating at instantiation time "here's the 3.0.1 template, give me one instance of this, and override these 2 settings". This is an operator issue. which is separate then the build step of the package, which is "I want to build package 2.0.1" and "I want to template out Chart.yaml so I don't have to tweak them all when I want to build 3.0.1 instead of 3.0.0" (or revision 3.0.1-1 or revision 3.0.1-2 ...)
[KF]Think of the pipeline:
[KF] 1. kolla releases 3.0.2 containers. 2. kolla releases helm 3.0.2 helm packages. 3. user 'helm update nova-novnc-proxy'
[KF] Step 1 and step 2 can be done by us. step 3 can be the end user, not having to do either step 1 or 2. They can optionally do it, if they want though.

But I'm kind of shying away from either approach. Individual packages are the most clean, clear and safe (orchestration free). They will better map "helm upgrade <packagename>" at the microservice level so advanced tooling built on top of helm should support microservice level packages better. (some day "helm upgrade all" for z stream updates)

[SB] Individual packages are great, agree, but it should not be the only option to deploy a microservice! Each microservice should be deployed with two ways as packages and just chart.
[KF] What is the problem with deploying with packages? what advantage is doing it just from a chart? Is a second long build step really that onerous? Is the tradeoff on being able to deploy from raw files so much better to pay for the extra overhead?

2. Management overhead. This approach requires dozens of files (after all services converted) to be touched to update a version number. Chart.yaml and values.yaml can not be templated in helm, but for our project, templating them would be very important to not have so much management overhead. We only have so much help. I believe we need to template them all, which requires a build step other then 'helm package'. Once we accept we need to do that, then other things, like filesystem layout are no longer dependent on what helm package requires. So we can make a kolla-kubernetes/templates/<servicename>/<microservicename>.yaml and compile them into their respective packages rather then be restricted to what helm must have for a layout. Ideally, I would want to build a new package for every microservice for every z stream container update I do. This really would require templating or operators will suffer. Again, this would enable the "helm upgrade all" for z stream update use case)

[SB] Rendering values.yaml and Chart.yaml is nice, but what is the source for them??
[KF] The stuff we provide. Is the same as what is in yours, but just arranged differently.

3. Globals seem to me, an unplesent way to expose primary configuration of a package. The var names are already unique enough, the names are long to begin with without needing the prefix, and its unclear how you even specify the globals. I'd guess like:
helm install foo --set global.docker_registry=localhost:4000,global.docker_namespace=region1,global.kolla_base_distro=ubuntu,kolla_install_type=binary
? (with a dot?) ....
#the globals really add up fast.
It also suffers the inability to override at a microservice level. 

[SB] you can override values at every levels with this approach as well as with command line
[KF] How do you build a pure microservice package with this approach? I don't see a way to do it.

If you 'helm install nova' you can't override the settings on nova-novncproxy without overriding the settings on every other microservice. 

[SB] that is not true. You can override setting at values.yaml at nova-novncproxy
[KF] no, see pipeline above. As an operator, I don't want to have to customize source(yaml) files in subpackages. Making an operator touch source feels very wrong to me. I should be able to interact with helm with prebuild packages to override settings.

This lessened flexibility will cause operators problems. It will have even more problems when you make 3 level packages such as openstack->nova->nova-api. globals there leak across everywhere. They aren't quite scoped right for the use case I think.

[SB] Globals were introduced exactly for this reason, to be able to have definition at the common place and then override at lower levels. 
[KF] Yup, and they were introduced very recently without testing at a scale we're attempting to deploy them at. I think they are very wrong for this use case. They certainly have a use case and a good thing to have in the toolbox though.

To me, the most important thing is getting the package granularity right, and the variable api defined, as we will have to support the api for a the long haul. The machinery for building the packages to provide a clean package api, can be ugly for now, until helm gains better machinery of its own.

[SB] I agree what was proposed is not the most efficient way, but your PoC far from being optimial, the only reason I did not -2 because I saw an alternative way for me to move forward. 
[KF] Yup. I admit mine isn't either. thats why its a PoC and I asked for discussion. Now we're having it. which is a good thing. :)

So, lets come up with a design that:
1. has clean vars api contract that we can support for a long time.
2. modular from a microservice package to a wrapping service package, to a wrapping whole openstack package.

[SB] I do not think we need to develop a complete wrapping service. If we need to deal with values.yaml and Chart.yaml let's deal with  them without inventing  the particles accelerator
[KF] Some people requested specifically the ability to deploy a whole openstack using just a helm package. The desire is there and strong. Just because you and I don't agree with that approach, that we should design the system in such a way that makes it impossible to implement. I think we can come up with a way that will allow everyone to do it their own way and be happy working together, rather then alienate and cause more competing projects to come about.

3. templated for ease of maintenance/quick releases by us&operators.
4. maximizes code reuse/minimizes copy&paste coding.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-11-28 19:42:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

> > @Pete, I can propose to invite some helm developers to irc or to
 > > join their developers meeting this thursday to directly discuss
 > > this functionality.
 > 
 > It would be great to get them in the channel, if they were up for
 > that - I'm sure that we could learn a lot from each other.

+1. that would be great."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2016-11-28 19:43:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

can we not -2 reviews unless they are flat out wrong?  The proper approach is two +2 votes without any core reviewer dissent.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-11-28 19:45:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-11-28 20:09:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

> Reposted as my last set of comments got merged with the quotes..
 > 
 > > 1. I need to be able to launch and customize each microservice
 > all
 > > on its own. I would like to run them as individual helm instances
 > > on my system so that one microservice update can't affect any
 > > other. So, 0% orchestration by helm at the services level. This
 > > arrangement does not support that. While https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/issues/1568#issuecomment-262086504
 > > shows an approach on how a client based plugin mechanism might
 > > work, but that can also be done in the helm chart itself as
 > > prototyped in my helm chart poc. I'd rather the templating system
 > > do it then the client. But I'm kind of shying away from either
 > > approach. Individual packages are the most clean, clear and safe
 > > (orchestration free). They will better map "helm upgrade
 > > <packagename>" at the microservice level so advanced tooling
 > built
 > > on top of helm should support microservice level packages better.
 > > (some day "helm upgrade all" for z stream updates)
 > 
 > 
 > [PB] I think you raise some good points here, though I think the
 > solution suggested in https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/issues/1568#issuecomment-262394195,
 > may work provide rather than excluding packages we specific which
 > subpackage we actually want to install. If we could do 'helm
 > upgrade openstack --subpackage="swift/proxy"' would that alivate
 > your concerns?

[KF] What I'm trying to do is enable a layer cake to be built. so, on a redhat machine, if you trust your distro to only provide minor upgrades (most do), you can stick "yum upgrade -y" in a cronjob.

[KF] With this, ultimately, I want to do the same. Add a k8s scheduled job that does a 'helm upgrade' that will upgrade all updated instantiations. If its done as a subpackage like that, I'm worried bugs will creep in where more then just the bits that need updating will get updated. what happens when you upgrade a package that was instantiated with only a subpackage? The package layer should be simple to understand. Selective subpackaging is not.

[KF] The whole idea seems a little backwards to me. Just make the subpackages real packages and be done with it. Why try and work through a parent package just to get the one subpackage you want to launch? The reason is lacking features of the current system. There isn't a totally clean way to share things between packages, so we're moving the bits up to a parent package to try and share it. The tail is wagging the dog. Lets not do that on something we want to maintain for the long haul. Lets do it right, then figure out how to get helm feature enough so that its clean too.

 > 
 > 
 > 
 > > 2. Management overhead. This approach requires dozens of files
 > > (after all services converted) to be touched to update a version
 > > number. Chart.yaml and values.yaml can not be templated in helm,
 > > but for our project, templating them would be very important to
 > not
 > > have so much management overhead. We only have so much help. I
 > > believe we need to template them all, which requires a build step
 > > other then 'helm package'. Once we accept we need to do that,
 > then
 > > other things, like filesystem layout are no longer dependent on
 > > what helm package requires. So we can make a kolla-kubernetes/templates/<servicename>/<microservicename>.yaml
 > > and compile them into their respective packages rather then be
 > > restricted to what helm must have for a layout. Ideally, I would
 > > want to build a new package for every microservice for every z
 > > stream container update I do. This really would require
 > templating
 > > or operators will suffer. Again, this would enable the "helm
 > > upgrade all" for z stream update use case)
 > 
 > 
 > [PB] I both agree and disagree with you here :) As helm stands I
 > think that we will inevitably need to introduce some sort of
 > templating system to process the values.yaml, and version
 > numbering. However I think it would be counterproductive to move
 > away from the standard helm chart layout. I believe that any
 > templating we do should be as minimal as possible, and should just
 > prepare the tree to the point where a (or several) 'helm package'
 > is possible, as this will reduce the burdon on us to produce
 > tooling, provide a lower barrier of entry to users to the project,
 > and hopefully allow us to retire any such feature as helm matures.

[KF] I'm good with that. Like I said, Im much more concerned with how the packages get used, and to a lesser extent, not duplicating a lot of code and then the exact layout of the file system.

 > 
 > 
 > 
 > > 3. Globals seem to me, an unplesent way to expose primary
 > > configuration of a package. The var names are already unique
 > > enough, the names are long to begin with without needing the
 > > prefix, and its unclear how you even specify the globals. I'd
 > guess
 > > like:
 > > helm install foo --set global.docker_registry=localhost:4000,global.docker_namespace=region1,global.kolla_base_distro=ubuntu,kolla_install_type=binary
 > > ? (with a dot?) ....
 > > #the globals really add up fast.
 > 
 > 
 > [PB] The example you have above is indeed pretty horrible - and why
 > I think we will end up wrapping helm for real deployments.

[KF] Yup. But this is something we will have to live forever with, so lets try and get it right, rather then try and kludge our use case into essentially what is a (1.0.0) feature. (lightly tested in the real world.) Lets make the api proper.

 > 
 > 
 > 
 > > It also suffers the inability to override at a microservice
 > level.
 > > If you 'helm install nova' you can't override the settings on
 > > nova-novncproxy without overriding the settings on every other
 > > microservice. This lessened flexibility will cause operators
 > > problems. It will have even more problems when you make 3 level
 > > packages such as openstack->nova->nova-api. globals there leak
 > > across everywhere. They aren't quite scoped right for the use
 > case
 > > I think.
 > 
 > 
 > [PB] This is somthing we will need to review - I've thought of a
 > potenital solution, but I'm not sure (using nova as an example): We
 > include config generation at the service level package or a
 > nova/config subpackage, so users who run 'helm install nova' would
 > get an opinionated deployment with sane defaults. Microservice/sub-packages
 > would not include any confiuration allowing us full controll.

[KF] Thats what I was thinking too. That works for openstack config files, but not the config options to particular microservices templates themselves, which is what I'm trying to address.

[KF] What if I want to do the following:
[KF] helm install nova --set compute.enable_kube_logger=True,api.enable_kube_logger=False
[KF] ? As an op, I'm sure I'd want to be able to do that kind of thing.

 > 
 > 
 > > To me, the most important thing is getting the package
 > granularity
 > > right, and the variable api defined, as we will have to support
 > the
 > > api for a the long haul. The machinery for building the packages
 > to
 > > provide a clean package api, can be ugly for now, until helm
 > gains
 > > better machinery of its own.
 > 
 > 
 > [PB] It's for this reason I'm heavily in favor of adopting a model
 > that tracks the 'helm' way of doing things as closley as possible -
 > as though the code may not be so elegant initally it stands a
 > better chance of long term survivability without creating out own
 > rabbit warren.

[KF] I'm all for including the helm devs in the loop of our trying to use helm as an orchestration tool. I think its much more complicated then they have ever done before though, so I'm sure it wont work without some number more months of development to fill in gaps with something as complicated as openstack. So I don't think we stop now and wait for all required features to merge. (same thing with k8s itself). We try and do it as well as we can with the tool, and when it breaks, we file issues and work around it until its supported, then fix our code to do thing the upstream way.

[KF] There are those that also don't want helm to do any orchestration at all. Just templating at instantiation time. So we have to support those two use cases as well. 

 > 
 > > So, lets come up with a design that:
 > > 1. has clean vars api contract that we can support for a long
 > time.
 > > 2. modular from a microservice package to a wrapping service
 > > package, to a wrapping whole openstack package.
 > > 3. templated for ease of maintenance/quick releases by
 > > us&operators.
 > > 4. maximizes code reuse/minimizes copy&paste coding.
 > 
 > 
 > [PB]  These are the goals we should work towards for sure. :)

[KF] Yeah. I'm trying to get agreement on the goals, then we can work on what the best way to achieve them. We've been trying to argue implementation rather then define the problem, which I think is tripping us up a bit.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-11-28 20:12:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

> > [SB] Only now, with helm 2.1 introduced, we can render at each
 > > level, global kolla-kubernetes, or service or microservice.
 > 
 > Do you have any further info on this proposed feature? it's pretty
 > critical to any decision making we take. The only info I can find
 > about the future of helm is here: https://github.com/kubernetes/helm/wiki/Roadmap

Likewise, do we know roughly their timescale? Is this 1 month, 6, or somewhere in between? cause if its more then a month, we probably don't want to wait."}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-11-28 20:15:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I was told that helm 2.1 would be release soon after the holidays. We can get more firm date sometime this week.'}, {'account_id': 23928, 'date': '2016-11-28 22:31:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

This IRC log, has a lot of discussion relevant to this (and https://review.openstack.org/#/c/396296/) review: http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-kolla/%23openstack-kolla.2016-11-28.log.html#t2016-11-28T20:13:13'}, {'account_id': 23928, 'date': '2016-11-29 01:12:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7769, 'date': '2016-11-29 17:44:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
WIP Hierarchical approach for helm charts

This PS introduce an alternative approach in storing helm chart. The top
of hierarchy is kolla-kubernetes, with childs as main openstack services
and sub-childs as microservices. This approach allows to keep global
variables at parent level, service specific variables at service level
and sub-child variable at corresponding sub-child level. with HELM 2.1
we will be able to deploy a single microservice but with all variables
defined at parent and child levels, which makes it very flexible.

Change-Id: I5739dea54a888eb660dd44d0f496a8ec81f1565e
Partially-Implements: blueprint helm-packaging

DO_NOT_MERGE PoC Configmap update monitor

This PS is PoC of one of possible solution for implementing
config change propagation to POD running a service which consumes
configuration from its configmap.

Can you add a doc change to specify the specific version of ceph that one must use?  Hammer release?

I'm using Infernalis by the way.  It'd be good if we could make it on both. Technically, Infernalis is newere than Hammer and we would be taking a step back.  I'm not going to -1 based on requiring Hammer, so long as the requirement is documented in the RST files."}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-08-23 18:24:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Whats kolla's take on upgrading ceph? Jewel is out and its their new lts. hammer was the old lts and its very long in the tooth now."}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2016-08-23 18:27:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'll have to bring it up at the next meeting.  The reason I landed on hammer is I used kolla-ansible to deploy ceph.  I'm all for using what is newest, but this is also the latest packaged version I could find.  We may want to stay close to what's in packages unless we specify otherwise in the docs.  I'm up for either option."}, {'account_id': 22143, 'date': '2016-08-23 18:29:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

I use ceph-ansible to deploy ceph.'}, {'account_id': 22143, 'date': '2016-08-23 18:30:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Oh yeah, Hammer LTS has been superceded by Jewel LTS.  Hammer is pretty old.

http://docs.ceph.com/docs/master/releases/'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-08-23 18:32:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

for my test system, I'm using kolla's ceph containers manually deployed with k8s. for the production system I want to eventually get kolla-kubernetes on, it will be jewel."}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-08-23 18:34:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Latest Ceph client flag changed for layering

To enable layering, the flag changed to --image-features
accepting an integer. The int 1 is for layering.

Change-Id: Ib7ba779c1be8226652322c44364a06717b211b9e

commit_message:
Neutron create mariadb failed with wrong login host

Neutron create mariadb bootstrap will using ##neutron_database_address##
variable as mariadb login host. But the default value was defined in
kolla-ansbile neutron's default variable file. It is "{{
kolla_internal_fqdn }}:{{ database_port }}"

This will cause the login host will be something like "mariadb:3306" It
should be "mariadb" instead of "mariadb:3306" We can just rewrite this
to "mariadb", just like other services (ex: nova or cinder) which how to
create db.

Change-Id: Ib02f3dad80219e13166a58eeb78dee0cabddd8ec
Closed-Bug: 1670318

[{'created': '2017-03-08 08:54:13.000000000', 'message': '[helm]Create keystone public service failed with nil external vip

When user try to install keystone-public-svc with default value.
Helm will installed failed with following messages

$ helm install microservice/keystone-public-svc
Created tunnel using local port: '41270'
SERVER: "localhost:41270"
CHART PATH: /home/lyan/helm/microservice/keystone-public-svc
Error: error validating "": error validating data: unexpected nil value
for field spec.externalIPs[0]

Keystone-public-svc will default enable external port, this will cause
svc yaml will need to get externa_vip value. But it will not been assign
any value. Therefore the svc yaml will output:

```
externalIPs:
    -
```

Maybe we should check whether external port had been enable and external vip had been added,
then assign external vip.

Change-Id: If74b97036d451420a2dbfef2786d9015657a47ac
Closed-Bug: 1670979
'}]
commit_message:
[helm]Create keystone public service failed with nil external vip

When user try to install keystone-public-svc with default value.
Helm will installed failed with following messages

$ helm install microservice/keystone-public-svc
Created tunnel using local port: '41270'
SERVER: "localhost:41270"
CHART PATH: /home/lyan/helm/microservice/keystone-public-svc
Error: error validating "": error validating data: unexpected nil value
for field spec.externalIPs[0]

Keystone-public-svc will default enable external port, this will cause
svc yaml will need to get externa_vip value. But it will not been assign
any value. Therefore the svc yaml will output:

```
externalIPs:
    -
```

Maybe we should check whether external port had been enable and external vip had been added,
then assign external vip.

Change-Id: If74b97036d451420a2dbfef2786d9015657a47ac
Closed-Bug: 1670979

Re-version helm after a release

This tool makes it easy after a commit hash is chosen for
tagging to change the version number rather then scramble prior
to choosing a tag to change version numbers.

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 21996, 'date': '2016-06-06 17:57:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Oh, and to explain Keith's comment...  In the Kubernetes environment, we can use SkyDNS to not only look up the IP address to connect to (thus saving us from hardcoding IP addresses that will change) but we can also look up the SRV record or environment variable to look up the port number -- See http://kubernetes.io/docs/user-guide/services/#dns for reference.

In our case, this would be somewhat the opposite of the traditional templatized approach where the port number is set in a config file and all of the generated templates have the port number added.  This is, frankly, less important because the port number isn't exactly going to be changing all of the time and the DNS lookup requires extra steps to be executed, although it does make the system more resilient to eccentric misconfiguration issues.

Looking at the service yaml files we've already generated, I would suggest that we require that services be named instead of just unnamed port numbers."}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-06-08 12:51:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-06-08 13:13:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Kolla Kubernetes Service Discovery BP

The scope of this BP is to make use of existing dynamic dns
functionality in Kubernetes and to introduce the service naming
convention which should be followed while generating service
configuration files.

Implements: Kolla Kubernetes Service Discovery

Change-Id: I03aae9545d1b8cd7b4d695e33434cf6b8cf53d4e

commit_message:
[WIP] Condition and tags in requirements.yaml for keystone service

Use condition and tags feature for requirements.yaml in Helm 2.2 for
standalone keystone service installation
The dependency chart mariadb can be enabled/disabled upon user's choice.

Partially implements: blueprint condition-and-tags

Change-Id: I0a1a9777c1944af404a62676bbbe5b898a692e53

Takashi,

Thank you for the contribution!  I am -2ing this review, not becuase it is wrong, but because our upstream development environment tool (halcyon) is unmaintained.   We are removing the development environment we have in place (halycon) and starting over on a new development environment.  In the meantime, if you want to do local development, I'd recommend reading these docs:
https://docs.openstack.org/developer/kolla-kubernetes/deployment-guide.html

If you are interested in working on the development environment, there is this blueprint to track a new development environment.  For the moment, the gate is the best development environment available, as it has very thorough testing of the code.  It does take a bit of getting used to (to execute the workflow).

If you are keen to contribute to the new revision of the development environment, I'd invite you to contact spurya on irc in #openstack-kolla who is leading this blueprint:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/kolla-kubernetes/+spec/devenv-taketwo"}, {'account_id': 7488, 'date': '2018-06-07 09:33:25.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Kube Util could not get api url from kubeconfig

Kube Util could not get api url from kubeconfig when cluster name is not
match with current-context

Current code flow will iterator each cluster in kube config, and then
find matched name with current context. The cluster's server could not
been found if cluster name is not match with current context. We should
find match context name instead cluster name, and then using context's
cluster name to find cluster. Finally get the cluster's server

Change-Id: Ia8a5004552e47e2216fe6413e0359a0df59a3d4e
Closed-Bug: 1669788

commit_message:
Add --debug to all ceph workflows in gate

The ceph workflows lacked a --debug in helm output.  This doesn't
permit the display of the computed helm charts.  This is a
general improvement to the gate for consistency.

Change-Id: I9e5336f57365f885d2aaa408b76dec18c1d6eab5
Partially-Implements: blueprint gate-continuous-improvement

commit_message:
A start at a simplified devtool environment

We have wasted *TWO* months or more of time attempting to integrate
the development environment with the main gate.  Instead of doing
that, lets start small with a set of scripts based upon the
deployment guide which was built based upon learning how the
gate operates.

The intent is to follow this up with a gate specifically for the
development environment workflow.  I know this is far from perfect.
THe idea is for folks to build on this work in an incremental fashion.
As such, I'd ask for a little liency in the review process.

This will ultimatelly integrate with
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/457042/

Change-Id: I90671b4894f0024d3b094c8459edf61e1acfe04a

WIP Fixing ironic deployment failure on Ubuntu

Due to some particularities of libvirtd on Ubuntu, it runs with nova user
privileges. It breaks virsh commands runing from the host.

WIP: Cache k8s

the gate from sudden changes in the released binaries.

commit_message:
Change ordering of PV retrieval

In some conditions (such as service charts) the PVs are deleted
by the helm delete iteration.  To solve that, capture the list of
PVs after helm delete occurs.  This works for either service charts
or microchart deployments.

Change-Id: Ia7586c4c7b96c100f52ad682d21145fb654c72bd

sbezverk,

You must admit it is very odd to see a pvc named mariadb mounted against a volume named glance.  Further, on redeploy (of selected comoponents) with existing PVs, the PVC isn't consistently mapped to the proper PV.

That is why labels for this exist in kubernetes."}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2017-06-01 15:56:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

It is a problem with naming
PV should be name pv-10g-1 pv-20g-1 etc or something like that and not using service name.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2017-06-01 16:08:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It seems a bit incomplete. This may be relevant https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/42503

Serguei is right in that admins should be creating them rather then users. and ideally we would support dynamic storage classes....

That said, as a batteries included case where the user doesn't have a dynamic provisioner, the admin=user, and just wants everything to work and look sane, this seems like a good feature to support. having them in the default pool means users might snag them before kolla is finished deploying. We may want to create a different storage class for kolla ones?"}, {'account_id': 7488, 'date': '2018-06-07 09:33:07.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add Apache License Content in index.rst

1. What is the problem?
Apache License 2.0 is lack in ./releasenotes/source/index.rst

2. What is the solution to the problem?
Add Apache License 2.0 Content which is necessary
for ./releasenotes/source/index.rst.

3. What the features need to be implemented to the Tricircle to realize the solution?
No need

Change-Id: I6ce6be335b9bb361541f7eaead7d0f0b59434b47

commit_message:
Script to clean up kolla-kubernetes node labels

Since similar task seems very difficult to program in ansible,
I suggest to call this script right from the ansible destroy workflow
and enjoy the ride.

Change-Id: Icc3725dfdf1532c3d54e1d041700638bac7b5499

subject: Add nova and libvirt PV/PVCs
messages:
[{'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2017-06-05 20:45:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2017-06-05 21:07:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't think this will work. each of the data locations has to be specific to the host to function right. I'm not sure a pv/pvc can ever be made to handle that without always being hostPath backed, which means a bunch of work for the admin for no real benefit.

Looking at the docs a little bit, nfs is supported as an option and it looks like /var/lib/nova/instances is the location to share. Maybe an optional pv/pvc at that one location is a good idea though?"}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2017-06-05 21:27:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2017-06-05 21:58:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-06-05 22:28:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Support for increasing thread cache size in TCMalloc.

Currently TCMalloc's default tc size is 32MB.
This causes poor performance in ceph storage.
A new ceph_tcmalloc_tc_bytes option has been added
with a default of 128MB.

128 MB is default TC size at above jewel version.
and if we don't set this config,
osd daemon will running with 32 MB.
because 32MB is default size in TCmalloc 2.4 version.
32MB and 128MB are twice the performance difference.
- reference : https://www.slideshare.net/Red_Hat_Storage/
ceph-performance-projects-leading-up-to-jewel-61050682

Closes-Bug: #1698249
Change-Id: I85f87c9b859c7ee4d3dfd3eade98896b24f1139a
Signed-off-by: jangseon ryu <jangseon.ryu@navercorp.com>

So maybe it's better to keep the original path: /var/run.

3. BTW, when will the final official path be released? :)"}, {'account_id': 26553, 'date': '2017-10-31 06:04:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

the final patch'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2017-10-31 15:47:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

> 1. As a released stable version, kubernetets v1.8.0 is more
 > fitable.
 > 2. one suggestion:
 > As defined in the specification Linux FHS (Filesystem Hierarchy
 > Standard), path ./run is located in the path /var to place variable
 > files.

Unfortunately the FHS hasn't kept up with the times exactly. /var/run is a symlink to /run these days on most distro's. This ps fixes the fact that the symlink was accidentally passed through and not the directory from the host.

 > So maybe it's better to keep the original path: /var/run.
 > 
 > 3. BTW, when will the final official path be released? :)

Once its passing the tests."}, {'account_id': 26553, 'date': '2017-11-01 08:54:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Code-Review+1

writing convention: do not use “-y” for package install

https://docs.openstack.org/contributor-guide/ for details

subject: Fix hostname in rabbitmq-clusterer.config
revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-07 12:34:31.000000000', 'message': 'Fix hostname in rabbitmq-clusterer.config

The hostname is determined when generating config files using
kolla-ansible, so it need to be replaced with one in /etc/hosts of a
rabbitmq container.

Change-Id: I1934b6b1c62330dde467b16705368c3b14fd4378
'}]
commit_message:
Fix hostname in rabbitmq-clusterer.config

The hostname is determined when generating config files using
kolla-ansible, so it need to be replaced with one in /etc/hosts of a
rabbitmq container.

Change-Id: I1934b6b1c62330dde467b16705368c3b14fd4378

commit_message:
WIP Dockerfile to run ansible orchiestration

When we move to ansible orchiestration, we want it to run on k8s.
That means we need container with it.

Change-Id: I02bc0bc314ed29fae172cea189d064b4bbd2ff76

Step1 seems straightforward to me.  This step introduces complexity, b/c we're only included parts of the config into each chart.  It would seem like this would be easy to get wrong and lead to many questions along the lines of, "I added this config to values.yaml, why isn't it showing up in my chart".  Since the values are already pretty heavily namespaced in values.yaml, why not include everything?  I guess I'm missing the benefit this extra granularity buys us?'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2017-09-25 15:43:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

> Step1 seems straightforward to me.  This step introduces
 > complexity, b/c we're only included parts of the config into each
 > chart.  It would seem like this would be easy to get wrong and lead
 > to many questions along the lines of, "I added this config to
 > values.yaml, why isn't it showing up in my chart".  Since the
 > values are already pretty heavily namespaced in values.yaml, why
 > not include everything?  I guess I'm missing the benefit this extra
 > granularity buys us?

The idea is to make it really easy to tell what values are affecting what charts. And to only have one place to set the values in our code base.  When we have lots of extra values leaking into each chart, there is no easy way to know what values affect which charts and which are just dead values. If we have them explicitly stated in each chart, once helm gains the 'download values.yaml' feature it will generate a values.yaml file for the user to fill in with just the values that apply to that particular chart. I think this will enhance usability.'}, {'account_id': 9927, 'date': '2017-09-26 01:43:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

> The idea is to make it really easy to tell what values are
 > affecting what charts. And to only have one place to set the values
 > in our code base.  When we have lots of extra values leaking into
 > each chart, there is no easy way to know what values affect which
 > charts and which are just dead values. If we have them explicitly
 > stated in each chart, once helm gains the 'download values.yaml'
 > feature it will generate a values.yaml file for the user to fill in
 > with just the values that apply to that particular chart. I think
 > this will enhance usability.

Ok I think I follow this now.  There will be will a single file (+100) with all the values in it.  Then each chart says, "I need this value",  or "I need that value" and pulls in what it needs.  I guess the only thing that I fuzzy on is the namespace structure in the values.yaml file.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-10-09 19:55:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

commit_message:
Helm Native Values Step 2.

This PS converts most of the rest of all_values.yaml
to helm parent values stored in the kolla-common chart.

Change-Id: I773c9e0310beb55939625e5a8e3dc13d462ef768

Helm Native Values Step 1.

This PS starts converting away from generating microservices
values.yaml to building it using the helm native parent
values feature.

commit_message:
Make registry available

This will be required for more advanced orch work - putting ansible in
containers. Also first step to move gates to tarball-based images.

Change-Id: Ic75b81efd365a3d1fcd2fc658f4798cc5edd6d48

commit_message:
WIP: Add support for HTTPS on external API network

This patch enables the use of HTTPS for the OpenStack API by
using HAProxy to provide TLS termination.  Both the configuration
and the documentation for the deployment guide are updated with
this optional feature.

This patch is still in progress.

Next step is to update the Keystone catalog entries with https://
instead of http:// for those services presenting with TLS.

For the initial patch, only the services that currently use
HAProxy will support TLS.

Co-Authored-By: Kevin Fox <kevin@efox.cc>

Change-Id: I2ee6a379c424b2aaa7780dc412211496afe8f5b1

commit_message:
Simple configmap to raw kubectl

Generate simple configmaps using just kubectl. This removes
most of the remaining uses of kollakube.

Change-Id: I98984be44e53cc24faedba53844785cd0b2080a1

commit_message:
Remove development environment

Halcyon is not actively maintained.  As a result, we need a
different approach to a development environment.  This first
step removes the existing unmaintained development environment.

Change-Id: Ib668ee372add42a43152252d993f8eaed0ddb261
Partially-Implements: blueprint devenv-taketwo

Just to recap what we discussed in irc a bit, This has some imperative logic between the user and the operator. We should have the request from the user be declarative only "I want a memcached on port 888" rather then request explicitly a how. "I want a memcached on port 888 and deploy it (state=deploy)" The latter is implied by the user creating the request and the requested memcached not existing on the cluster. The opposite happens on delete. if the memcache exists but the request for it doesn't, it should be deleted. This is more natural then the user putting in a new request object with a state=delete.'}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2017-01-11 23:02:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-01-11 23:03:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified-1

python based operator for memcached, includes 3 major components:
1. Kubernetes 3rd party object, which define MemcachedOperator kind
2. Kubernetes definition of memcached-operator. This object allows
   communication between some entity controlling entity, could be
   a human operator or some orchestration and memcached-operator
   executing agent.
3. Python script of memcached-operator execution agent. It monitors
   changes in the state of memcached-operator object and reacts
   accordingly.

commit_message:
WIP memcached operator

python based operator for memcached, includes 3 major components:
1. Kubernetes 3rd party object, which define MemcachedOperator kind
2. Kubernetes definition of memcached-operator. This object allows
   communication between some entity controlling entity, could be
   a human operator or some orchestration and memcached-operator
   executing agent.
3. Python script of memcached-operator execution agent. It monitors
   changes in the state of memcached-operator object and reacts
   accordingly.

Change-Id: Icbe68245e8ffc68a1617047c5aa34915d2404681

commit_message:
Seperate kolla and kolla-ansible search paths

Add method to find  kolla-ansible path
Add dictionary variable for ymls
Add array variable for roles
Fix variable name from kolla_dir to kolla_ansible_dir

Change-Id: Icf1394cf13f8a8b149540c85c203e3eb47cfe67c

I would be okay with no petset for the moment, since it follows existing patterns.  We do have to go back and make mariadb and glance a petset.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-09-11 23:14:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 17591, 'date': '2016-10-30 18:33:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> I would be okay with no petset for the moment, since it follows
 > existing patterns.  We do have to go back and make mariadb and
 > glance a petset.

I spoke with Nadeem and he said it'd be okay to take this over and finish it for him.  To align with Kevin's comment, should we go ahead and make this a petset?  I think it'd be better to do it correctly now instead of having to go back and change it later"}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2016-10-31 08:59:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

kevin why does heat-engine need to be a petset?  Steve, I'll make sure the bp is assigned to you if it isn't already."}, {'account_id': 11869, 'date': '2016-10-31 11:49:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

hi,good commit please fix gate error'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-10-31 15:45:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Ryan: the heat-engine is an rpc based service. it registers itself in the database by hostname. as such petsets are a better fit as the hostname doesn't constantly change, cluttering the db. See:
heat service-list"}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-10-31 15:53:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

At this point, this code can be greatly simplified based on the services/common/* code.

heat-api could be done like neutron-server (Its purely in service_resources.yml) and the heat-engine can be done with a petset like services/nova/nova-control-scheduler-pod.yml.j2

the -service.yml.j2's can go away and use the common code and the bootstrap code can use the common endpoint bits in service_resources and just need a couple of files like: services/neutron/*bootstrap*.yml.j2"}, {'account_id': 17591, 'date': '2016-10-31 16:15:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> At this point, this code can be greatly simplified based on the
 > services/common/* code.
 > 
 > heat-api could be done like neutron-server (Its purely in
 > service_resources.yml) and the heat-engine can be done with a
 > petset like services/nova/nova-control-scheduler-pod.yml.j2
 > 
 > the -service.yml.j2's can go away and use the common code and the
 > bootstrap code can use the common endpoint bits in
 > service_resources and just need a couple of files like:
 > services/neutron/*bootstrap*.yml.j2

Alright, thanks Kevin.  I think I've got a handle on it with your description.  If I have any questions or concerns, I'll reach out through IRC."}, {'account_id': 17591, 'date': '2017-03-24 02:11:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Any update on this?'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2017-04-16 01:08:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-2

Md Nadeem,

Thank you for the contribution.  I'm not sure why it has taken so long for the core review team to communicate the helm adoption as it was done shortly after Barcelona Summit in November 2016.

The services/* directory is in the process of being removed as we have completely moved to helm.  Since services/* is essentially dead, I am -2'ing this review.  I would encourage you to abandon this review.  If you want to finish the job on Heat, I would recommend taking up this patch:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/437252/"}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2017-12-18 03:29:57.000000000', 'content': 'Removed reviewer Jenkins with the following votes:

* Verified-1 by Jenkins (3)
'}, {'account_id': 7488, 'date': '2018-06-07 09:29:37.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Remove all -1 from setup_gate.sh

-1 is not something bash returns.  Instead return a nonzero
value > 0 as per POSIX standards.

Change-Id: I59b2e7de605ddce9adaa6caadd2238dffe207d1c

Changing ALL pod to Deployments is wrong, as some will be PetSets, some are/will be DaemonSets. Please check first with people working on a specific component.'}, {'account_id': 16482, 'date': '2016-08-21 11:37:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> Changing ALL pod to Deployments is wrong, as some will be PetSets,
 > some are/will be DaemonSets. Please check first with people working
 > on a specific component.

I did see that MariaDB has a feature to become a PetSet so did not include it in the feature. As far as I can see, anything that is currently a replication controller or pod can logically be converted to a deployment without any issues (please correct me if I'm wrong).

When you say that some pods will be PetSets, they are not PetSets unless explicitly defined (unless explicit node deployment parameters are defined) which is also the case with DaemonSets.

What something WILL be is a different subject and I don't know what to do in that case? A component that will be a DaemonSet or a PetSet in the future does not effect the change as the transition of the current state to a Deployment should not cause any issues?

What are you referring to as a component? Is this a blueprint? or an OpenStack project implementation within kolla-kubernetes?

I would like to contribute to this project so any constructive feedback is appreciated."}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-08-21 11:43:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

There is currently active development for neutron and nova, please exclude all changes from your PS.
With all these changes, can you test them? Can you confirm that all these changes are working?'}, {'account_id': 16482, 'date': '2016-08-21 11:58:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

It is untested but I can test it. At the moment its purely theoretical based on Kubernetes docs. The changes are minor however adding a gate for testing would be the ideal solution. 

Would it be OK for me to add a gate for building and deploying kolla-kubernetes?'}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-08-21 12:01:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Having a gate for testing kube environment would be awesome. @Shaun: Thanks for working on this. I agree with Serguei. There are outstanding reviews for neutron/nova and I'd add glance to the list, refactoring them so please avoid those 3 for now.

Have a look at the various services, and if they show up in a service-list or an agent-list (nova service-list, neutron agent-list, heat service-list, etc) then those services should be made into a PetSet instead of a Deployment as the dns names matter.

Also, could you please review these two patch sets:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/354895/ - Example deployment that can seamlessly perform a rolling upgrade.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/357557/ - The host labeling mechanism should be generically useful. I'd like to adopt them everywhere if there's agreement.

I think #354895 is about ready for adoption to the other services. I would like to add the host labeling scheme from #357557 into it, and then I think its in great shape.

I had an idea this morning that, if the other service deployments were very similar to the one in #354895, maybe we could convert it to a generic template and make all of the openstack-api's call that instead. with something like:

etc/kolla-kubernetes/service_resources.yml:
      - name: glance-api-haproxy-configmap
        template: services/common/api-haproxy-configmap.yml.j2
        vars:
          configmap_name: glance-api-haproxy
          port_name: glance_api_port
      - name: glance-api-pod
        template: services/common/generic-api-pod.yml.j2
        vars:
          service_name: glance-api

Then do the rest of the services the same way.

What do you think? I haven't looked at all the deployments you did yet. I'll try and look tomorrow. Do they look very similar to each other? Would it be worth merging them together for easier maintenance?

Thanks, Kevin"}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-08-22 16:12:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I looked through, and really the ones that need to support rolling upgrades of the type in the other review are glance-api, glance-registry, cinder-api (don't have yet), heat-api (don't have yet), nova-api and neutron-server. So, really if we just exclude glance from here too I think we're good."}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-08-22 16:19:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

One concern I have with all these massive changes is that they are not tested. I think it would make more sense: 1. Get out base service as VM and connectivity running, 2. Develop gating, 3. Have fun with all these massive changes.
Until we have working base, all these, potentially can be changed if by some reason we discover that deployment, or pet sets or daemon sets cannot offer what we need.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-08-29 21:52:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

5 month old patch - is this still relevant?  If not, please abandon.'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2017-12-18 04:21:39.000000000', 'content': 'Removed reviewer Jenkins with the following votes:

- gate-kolla-kubernetes-deploy-ubuntu-source http://logs.openstack.org/96/333996/4/check/gate-kolla-kubernetes-deploy-ubuntu-source/55c676d/ : FAILURE in 2m 11s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 22143, 'date': '2016-06-27 22:26:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Kevin,

Based on the commit message, it kind of feels like we are working around something that should be fixed in horizon.  Could the web client check the horizon version?  Are there cache headers that horizon can set?

Nevertheless, I agree there may be a need to support canary or a/b deployments.  This may be the case for more components than Horizon.  In this case, I'd hope for a blueprint outlining a general pattern that can be followed.

For this existing implementation, it doesn't feel right embedding a version into everything.  Seems very intrusive.  If it has to be some kind of ID, an opaque identifier might do better, because you might not be deploying a different version, but a different configuration as well.

-1 until we understand more.

-dave"}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-06-28 02:14:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I don't think it can be solved in horizon as it would require horizon to support two versions at once (python doesn't really allow that) in the same webserver, or provide deployment scripts to allow two to run in parallel, which what this is, and in my opinion, the distro's job, as horizon's solution surely wouldn't be done in a container/k8s way.

I don't think cache headers would work, because horizon now dynamically loads pages as needed via Angular? So it may not have the entire site cached up front, so may get different versions.

I think horizon is probably the only service that will run into this issue? All the other services are rest api's and have ways to pin new api servers to older versions for compatibility until things are fully upgraded. rest api's are much easier to make support rolling upgrades then websites as rest api's don't usually keep persistent connections around, and are more accustomed to retrying automatically.

There isn't anything integer (or even number) specific about this solution. You can use tags if you'd prefer. So it can handle incompatible config changes too. I was originally thinking it was k8s cluster specific, just incrementing each time a new horizon was deployed, but doesn't have to be used that way. using 'a' and 'b' should work too."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-06-28 18:55:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-06-24 16:57:44.000000000', 'message': 'Horizon Versioning

Horizon is a web application that is distributed between the web
server, and the web browser. If the web server is upgraded while
the application is still running on the web browser, unusual issues
can creep up.

This patch allows multiple versions of Horizon to be run on
Kubernetes in parallel. Further patches will use this to direct
existing browser sessions at the version of Horizon they started on
to allow seamless major rolling upgrades.

Change-Id: Ib1d840aa10f02dfec6c89b7fa8a4fcf0ea204994

commit_message:
Support rolling upgrades of horizon

Horizon is a web application that is distributed between the web
server, and the web browser. If the web server is upgraded while
the application is still running on the web browser, unusual issues
can creep up.

This patch set allows multiple versions of Horizon to be run on
Kubernetes in parallel. It adds a Horizon frontend with session
tracking that allows the browser to continue to use the Horizon
version it was started with.

Change-Id: Ib1d840aa10f02dfec6c89b7fa8a4fcf0ea204994

> @Kevin, looks better but still I think not ideal, in this case we
 > have two references to keystone port, one in keyston svc section if
 > the use want to overwrite it, the second in nova cell0. Would it
 > not make it easier for the use to have a single reference? We
 > probably never run multiple instances of keystone but likely have
 > some genius who decides to override keystone default port. Making
 > it in global default section only if needed to override looks like
 > an easier option to support.

I think in that case, the users cloud.yaml would override them both by default with one value?

I agree, we should be making better use of groups though so that its only in the all_yaml once. but I think thats probably much easier solved once we retool on parent values. Ingress rolling upgrade support

This ps makes rolling upgrades follow the advice given by the nginx
ingress documentation here:
https://github.com/kubernetes/ingress/issues/322#issuecomment-298016539

commit_message:
Kubernetes Operator base

This patch includes:
  Base Kubernetes Operator class - kubernetes-operator.
  Base Service Kubernetes Operator class - service-operator.
  Kubernetes Operator Controller

The Kubernetes Operator container will execute the Controller
script consuming the yaml file 'operator.yaml'. 'operator.yaml'
will describe how the operator will run.

Change-Id: Ibbc9719455aa1d76a655fe73d22720ab765d191b
Partially-implements: blueprint operator-base

Closer. But I think it still has ways it will fail. for example if the ipmitool fails to power off the node, it still unlocks in this version leading to data corruption. There's also some unneeded conditionals and extra walks. I think simplifying the code will help with handling the edge cases.

I think the algorithm should be something like the following. (untested and mostly copy/pasted from the code here):

while true; do
  rbd --pool {{ storage_ceph['pool'] }} --conf /tmp/ceph/ceph.conf --keyring /tmp/ceph/ceph.keyring  ls > /tmp/volumes;
  kubectl get nodes -o json | jq -r '.items[] | select(.status.conditions[] | select(.type==\"Ready\" and .status!=\"True\")) | .metadata.name' | while read notready_node; do
    echo 'Checking volumes on the ceph cluster if failed node - ' $notready_node ' has kept lock for any';
    first_volume=1
    found_lock=0
    cat /tmp/volumes | while read volume;
      rbd_command_output=$(rbd --pool {{ storage_ceph['pool'] }} --conf /tmp/ceph/ceph.conf --keyring /tmp/ceph/ceph.keyring  lock ls $volume | grep client);
      id=$(echo $rbd_command_output | awk '{print $2}');
      client=$(echo $rbd_command_output | awk '{print $1}');
      host_name=${id/#kubelet_lock_magic_/};
      echo 'Checking '$volume '---'$id' - '$client' - '$host_name' - '$notready_node;
      if [ 'x$id' != 'x' -a 'x$client' != 'x' -a $notready_node == $host_name ]; then
        found_lock=1
        if [ $first_volume -eq 1 ]; then
          host_original=$notready_node;
          host_name=${host_original%%.*};
          host_suffics=${host_original#$host_name};
          host_ipmi=$host_name'-ipmi'$host_suffics;
          echo 'Killing power for - '$host_ipmi;
          ipmitool -H $host_ipmi -v -I lanplus -U $IPMIUSER -P $IPMIPASS chassis power off;
          if [ $? != 0 ]; then
            echo 'Failure to power off node - '$host_ipmi' error code -'$?;
            continue;
          echo 'Node - '$host_ipmi' has been powered off';
          first_volume=0;
        fi
        echo 'Found lock held by fenced node - '$notready_node;
        rbd --pool {{ storage_ceph['pool'] }} --conf /tmp/ceph/ceph.conf --keyring /tmp/ceph/ceph.keyring  lock remove $volume $id $client;
      fi
    done
    if [ $first_volume -eq 1 -a $found_lock = 1 ]; then
      echo Failed to power off node, skipping node.
      continue
    fi
  done
  sleep 1
done'}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-10-18 21:20:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28:

@Kevin, I tested current implementation and it is working well. I am ok to address some point issues but I do not see a reason for changing everything. Also in current implemention logic integrate cases when ipmitool just not used, as example with VM. No need to tell me that everybody have to use ipmitool, I will not. So unles you can come with a specific case where current implemention do not produce expected result, I would prefer to stay as is.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-10-18 23:01:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 28: Code-Review-1

-2. just because you "tested it" doesn't mean you hit all edge cases. I've hit a lot of "edge case" "that will never happen" in production.

Fencing code *MUST* be well written as it has a gun in one hand (ipmi), and a vial of poison in the other (the potential to corrupt system data by releasing locks). This is not the kind of code that you mess around with lightly.

I never said ipmi was a requirement. I plan on replacing that bit of code with an insteon bit of code for my home system. Fencing though, is. Otherwise there is no point in a fencing agent. In your vm case, you don't handle it yet at all. It needs an explicit 'nova shutdown' in that case, and its lacking. If you don't have that, then your just releasing the lock without proof that its safe to do so, and data corruption can occur.

The proposed rearrangement handles many more edge cases properly and doesn't restrict you from switching out the fencing agent (ipmi) with a different driver.

We can tweak the existing code to handle all the edge cases, but I think that will be quite difficult.'}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-10-18 23:37:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 28:

commit_message:
Fencing pod

This PS introduces fencing pod which:
1. Checks for status of kubernetes nodes
2. in case of a node failure it:
   2.1 Cleans CEPH locks
   2.2 Poweroff failed node via IPMI
   2.3 Clean up all Terminating PODs for faster failover

Change-Id: Iac47af9c9040f1128f0e5dbbb56bddbbaa15ecab
PartiallyImplements: blueprint kubernetes-toolbox

commit_message:
Helm charts for heat/heat-cfn create user and endpoints.

Add heat-create-keystone-endpoint-admin
    heat-create-keystone-endpoint-internal
    heat-create-keystone-endpoint-public
    heat-create-keystone-service
    heat-cfn-create-keystone-endpoint-admin
    heat-cfn-create-keystone-endpoint-internal
    heat-cfn-create-keystone-endpoint-public
    heat-cfn-create-keystone-service
    heat-create-keystone-user
Partially implements the heat.

Co-Authored-By: Balaji G Pattewar <balaji.pattewar@oracle.com>

Change-Id: I59d48ac37dd657394c92b3578505dfdd149ae21e
Partially-Implements: blueprint helm-microservices

commit_message:
Pull container tallballs into the gate

Pull containers from tarballs.oo to make gate more reliable.

This patch works by downloading the regitry from tarballs.oo, then
using the docker load operation to instantiate the tarballs.  Note
we use wget in this patch instead of curl as wget is far more reliable.

Depends-On: I7dcb6b2a8faf1ce74e10f73f6465f4c693031990
Change-Id: Ibc92755f20c4f4fcc1a0e13d7b2d58967a9dd5e9

commit_message:
Massive rework of the kolla-kubernetes docs

- Organize all the docs in an order that is easlier to read
- Shorten the quickstart and make AIO the default deployment
- Multinode will be considered 'advanced deployment'
- Remove unused docs

Change-Id: I544cbb422277b1dd3c3fecdfef67c496f92975d5

Add mandatory field to deployment document

For whatever reason, port must be specified for keystone.all in order
for cell0 registration to work.

commit_message:
add lower-constraints job

Create a tox environment for running the unit tests against the lower
bounds of the dependencies.

Create a lower-constraints.txt to be used to enforce the lower bounds
in those tests.

Add openstack-tox-lower-constraints job to the zuul configuration.

See http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2018-March/128352.html
for more details.

Change-Id: Ic1b777cf7d665615dce8efe3a96235f9162fc3bb
Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/555034
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

messages:
[{'account_id': 28009, 'date': '2018-03-28 06:57:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2018-03-28 06:57:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 7488, 'date': '2018-06-07 09:27:52.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2018-03-28 06:57:12.000000000', 'message': '    WSGI configuration missing directive

    WSGI configuration is missing the directive
    "WSGIApplicationGroup %{GLOBAL}" after
    WSGIProcessGroup" in the horizon template.
    Of all WSGI configuration templates it is
    the only one that does not have the
    "WSGIApplicationGroup" line.

    Closes-Bug: #1759488

Change-Id: Iccae0ddc00dffdb122aabca151f62c035a7b6f91
'}]
commit_message:
WSGI configuration missing directive

    WSGI configuration is missing the directive
    "WSGIApplicationGroup %{GLOBAL}" after
    WSGIProcessGroup" in the horizon template.
    Of all WSGI configuration templates it is
    the only one that does not have the
    "WSGIApplicationGroup" line.

    Closes-Bug: #1759488

Change-Id: Iccae0ddc00dffdb122aabca151f62c035a7b6f91

subject: Enable to use HA Kubernetes masters
messages:
[{'account_id': 24566, 'date': '2018-01-29 09:31:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2018-01-31 00:45:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Haproxy fronting everything is unnecessary for ha in kolla-kubernetes, as k8s itself is used for most of the functionality.

You can configure your openstack services already with an external IP of your keepalived vip. The kubernetes services are themselves load balancers that will automatically route the traffic to the right pods from that vip.

For the pods that use haproxy/apache internally, you can even do a rolling upgrade of them seamlessly today as k8s manages the membership of the load balancers and has readyness hooks that orchestrate the safe shutdown of the pods after traffic has stopped flowing to them.

Internally, it also uses k8s load balancers so service ha is already there that way too.'}, {'account_id': 24566, 'date': '2018-01-31 08:37:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> (1 comment)
 > 
 > Haproxy fronting everything is unnecessary for ha in
 > kolla-kubernetes, as k8s itself is used for most of the
 > functionality.
You are right, but currently, all services of kolla-k8s don't use DNS names but the IP of a master to access one another,
so in case of HA k8s masters, we should use the master cluster's VIP and need to set up haproxy in preparation for going down a master which kolla-k8s connects.
I am going to replace all master IPs with DNS names in conf files. 

 > You can configure your openstack services already with an external
 > IP of your keepalived vip. The kubernetes services are themselves
 > load balancers that will automatically route the traffic to the
 > right pods from that vip.
I used the charts for VIP

 > For the pods that use haproxy/apache internally, you can even do a
 > rolling upgrade of them seamlessly today as k8s manages the
 > membership of the load balancers and has readyness hooks that
 > orchestrate the safe shutdown of the pods after traffic has stopped
 > flowing to them.
 > Internally, it also uses k8s load balancers so service ha is
 > already there that way too.
I know, you advised me how haproxy/apache are operated, but my charts are not for each service but for clustered k8s master node.

 > helm/microservice/keepalived-daemonset/templates/keepalived-daemonset.yaml
 > Line 45:
 > This is important to allow users to override the specific device on a per host basis. in case your masters all don't share the same nic naming. (It happens)
You are right, it should be fixed.


If HA Kubernetes masters are already set up, in other words, a VIP for a master cluster is assigned 
and a reverse proxy for kube-api is installed, 
all we need to do are to configure the reverse proxy for all services 
and apply the VIP to kolla-k8s configuration files.

If not, we should install loadbalancer and reverse proxy to cluster masters using these helm charts,
and the next steps are to add master replicas, cluster etcd nodes and configure k8s cluster for HA
(The full details are beyond the scope of kolla-k8s, Refer to the following section for further details:
https://kubernetes.io/docs/admin/high-availability/)

You can install these helm charts without additional k8s master replicas and configuring k8s for HA for a test."}, {'account_id': 24566, 'date': '2018-01-31 11:03:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

1) Haproxy fronting everything is unnecessary for ha in kolla-kubernetes, as k8s itself is used for most of the functionality.
 -> You are right, but currently, all services of kolla-k8s don't use DNS names but the IP of a master to access one another, so in case of HA k8s masters, we should use the master cluster's VIP and need to set up haproxy in preparation for going down a master which kolla-k8s connects.
I am going to replace all master IPs with DNS names in conf files.

2) You can configure your openstack services already with an external IP of your keepalived vip. The kubernetes services are themselves load balancers that will automatically route the traffic to the right pods from that vip.
-> I used the charts for VIP

3) For the pods that use haproxy/apache internally, you can even do a rolling upgrade of them seamlessly today as k8s manages the membership of the load balancers and has readyness hooks that orchestrate the safe shutdown of the pods after traffic has stopped flowing to them.
Internally, it also uses k8s load balancers so service ha is already there that way too.
 -> I know, you advised me how haproxy/apache are operated, but my charts are not for each service but for clustered k8s master node.

helm/microservice/keepalived-daemonset/templates/keepalived-daemonset.yaml
This is important to allow users to override the specific device on a per host basis. in case your masters all don't share the same nic naming. (It happens)
 -> You are right, it should be fixed.


If HA Kubernetes masters are already set up, in other words, a VIP for a master cluster is assigned 
and a reverse proxy for kube-api is installed, 
all we need to do are to configure the reverse proxy for all services 
and apply the VIP to kolla-k8s configuration files.

If not, we should install loadbalancer and reverse proxy to cluster masters using these helm charts,
and the next steps are to add master replicas, cluster etcd nodes and configure k8s cluster for HA
(The full details are beyond the scope of kolla-k8s, Refer to the following section for further details:
https://kubernetes.io/docs/admin/high-availability/)

You can install these helm charts without additional k8s master replicas and configuring k8s for HA for a test."}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2018-01-31 17:22:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> 1) Haproxy fronting everything is unnecessary for ha in
 > kolla-kubernetes, as k8s itself is used for most of the
 > functionality.
 > -> You are right, but currently, all services of kolla-k8s don't
 > use DNS names but the IP of a master to access one another, so in
 > case of HA k8s masters, we should use the master cluster's VIP and
 > need to set up haproxy in preparation for going down a master which
 > kolla-k8s connects.

This is incorrect. They use the k8s service discovery mechanism for communication. The config points at the k8s service name. That resolves to the ClusterIP of the service. The Cluster IP is the load balancer for all the backend pods. So this is inherently HA.

 > I am going to replace all master IPs with DNS names in conf files.

You may have things misconfigured. it should already be pointing at k8s service dns names.

 > 2) You can configure your openstack services already with an
 > external IP of your keepalived vip. The kubernetes services are
 > themselves load balancers that will automatically route the traffic
 > to the right pods from that vip.
 > -> I used the charts for VIP

Yeah, the keepalived chart with a vip should be sufficient to provide the VIP and specifying it as the external vip should make all the services externally available.

 > 3) For the pods that use haproxy/apache internally, you can even do
 > a rolling upgrade of them seamlessly today as k8s manages the
 > membership of the load balancers and has readyness hooks that
 > orchestrate the safe shutdown of the pods after traffic has stopped
 > flowing to them.
 > Internally, it also uses k8s load balancers so service ha is
 > already there that way too.
 > -> I know, you advised me how haproxy/apache are operated, but my
 > charts are not for each service but for clustered k8s master node.

How the k8s control plane is setup should not effect the HA of kolla-kubernetes. You can co-locate the k8s control plane and the openstack one, but you don't have to. Openstack only relies on k8s services, so you actually can even create an HA openstack configuration with a single k8s master if you ensure the k8s master never runs anything but the k8s control plane. If the k8s master node dies, everything will continue working, meeting the HA definition.

 > helm/microservice/keepalived-daemonset/templates/keepalived-daemonset.yaml
 > This is important to allow users to override the specific device on
 > a per host basis. in case your masters all don't share the same nic
 > naming. (It happens)
 > -> You are right, it should be fixed.
 > 
 > 
 > If HA Kubernetes masters are already set up, in other words, a VIP
 > for a master cluster is assigned
 > and a reverse proxy for kube-api is installed,
 > all we need to do are to configure the reverse proxy for all
 > services
 > and apply the VIP to kolla-k8s configuration files.

No need for the reverse proxy. just set the external vip of the kolla-kubernetes services to that VIP.

If you really really want all the services to apear to be on the same port with a proxy in front, I'd strongly recommend using nginx-ingress rather then haproxy, as it much much more closely integrates with k8s.

 > If not, we should install loadbalancer and reverse proxy to cluster
 > masters using these helm charts,
 > and the next steps are to add master replicas, cluster etcd nodes
 > and configure k8s cluster for HA
 > (The full details are beyond the scope of kolla-k8s, Refer to the
 > following section for further details:
 > https://kubernetes.io/docs/admin/high-availability/)
 > 
 > You can install these helm charts without additional k8s master
 > replicas and configuring k8s for HA for a test.

....

I think part of the problem is, while we planned on writing some example reference architecture documents, we never had time to complete that work yet. Perhaps we should come up with an etherpad and scribble down some notes on getting that activity started? Kolla-Kubernetes has strived to use native k8s methodology whenever possible and there are a lot of things you can do with it if you know the tricks. Maybe just getting them down on paper would really help ensure we don't reinvent wheels k8s already provides?"}, {'account_id': 24566, 'date': '2018-04-18 13:11:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

As we talked on IRC several weeks ago, the installation guide I followed had had a mistake which causes configmaps not to use k8s service discovery mechanism, so we didn't understand each other.
Thank you for fixing it. (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/540196/)"}, {'account_id': 7488, 'date': '2018-06-07 09:27:48.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

In the case of adding new k8s master replicas to an existing k8s cluster
for HA, a load balancer and reverse proxy need to be set up.
Run these helm charts which install Keepalived using a VIP contained in
'kolla_internal_vip_address' and reverse proxy for all services of
kolla-k8s, after configuring some files below.
cloud.yaml
- Assigning VIP to "external_vip" and "dns_name"
/etc/kolla/global.yml
- Assigning VIP to "kolla_internal_vip_address"
- configure "api_interfase"
/etc/kolla-kubernetes/kolla-kubernetes.yml
- Assigning VIP to "kolla_kubernetes_external_vip"
- Assigning IPs of master replicas to "kolla_kubernetes_masters"
- Enable "HAProxy variables"
kolla-kubernetes/helm/all_values.yml
- Assigning VIP to "kolla_kubernetes_external_vip"
Enable binding to non-local IP addresses
$ echo "net.ipv4.ip_nonlocal_bind=1" >> /etc/sysctl.conf
$ sysctl -p

The final step is to configure k8s for HA, e.g. configuring the reverse
proxy for kube-api, clustering etcd servers and so on(The full details
are beyond the scope of kolla-k8s, Refer to the following section
for further details: https://kubernetes.io/docs/admin/high-availability/)).

You can install these helm charts without additional k8s master replicas
and configuring k8s for HA for a test.

'}]
commit_message:
Enable to use HA Kubernetes masters

In the case of adding new k8s master replicas to an existing k8s cluster
for HA, a load balancer and reverse proxy need to be set up.
Run these helm charts which install Keepalived using a VIP contained in
'kolla_internal_vip_address' and reverse proxy for all services of
kolla-k8s, after configuring some files below.
cloud.yaml
- Assigning VIP to "external_vip" and "dns_name"
/etc/kolla/global.yml
- Assigning VIP to "kolla_internal_vip_address"
- configure "api_interfase"
/etc/kolla-kubernetes/kolla-kubernetes.yml
- Assigning VIP to "kolla_kubernetes_external_vip"
- Assigning IPs of master replicas to "kolla_kubernetes_masters"
- Enable "HAProxy variables"
kolla-kubernetes/helm/all_values.yml
- Assigning VIP to "kolla_kubernetes_external_vip"
Enable binding to non-local IP addresses
$ echo "net.ipv4.ip_nonlocal_bind=1" >> /etc/sysctl.conf
$ sysctl -p

The final step is to configure k8s for HA, e.g. configuring the reverse
proxy for kube-api, clustering etcd servers and so on(The full details
are beyond the scope of kolla-k8s, Refer to the following section
for further details: https://kubernetes.io/docs/admin/high-availability/)).

You can install these helm charts without additional k8s master replicas
and configuring k8s for HA for a test.
