messages:
[{'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-07-29 19:25:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-07-29 19:37:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Published edit on patch set 1'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-07-29 22:40:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

How about this idea:

we label a set of nodes kolla-loadbalancer=v1
(this allows nodes to be also labeled kolla-compute=v1 or kolla-controller=v1, in all in 1 setups to co-locate)

We create a deamonset running net=host that lands on nodes labeled kolla-loadbalancer=v1. This allows the admin to easily scale up/down the set.

Each service we want to expose we tag with the external_ip flag on the service to the vip managed by keepalived.

we change all openstack services exposed with external_ip on their service to bind only to 127.0.0.1. Since OpenStack services don't do ssl termination very well, we setup a second container in each OpenStack service deployment (same pod) that is a haproxy instance. It listens on the port the service is bound to, not the openstack service itself, and it does the ssl termination, then forwards the traffic to 127.0.0.1. This co-schedulues the containers, and allows rolling upgrades."}, {'account_id': 19384, 'date': '2016-07-29 23:35:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

not sure if it efficient to extend ssl sessions to each individual service container instead of terminating all ssl at single point of entry like haproxy. Having large number of containers doing SSL termination will consume the cluster resource and limit the cluster's scale."}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2016-08-02 19:00:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'd think its the opposite? It would think scaling out the ssl infrastructure with the services would make it scale linearly rather then be bottle necked in one place.

Is the concern in the number of containers k8s has to manage?"}, {'account_id': 7462, 'date': '2016-09-05 17:01:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

In order to achieve service exposure:

- Create kubernettes services for each openstack service
- Set up an haproxy that redirects external requests to the k8s services either by DNS name or a by their port.

Additionaly there can be a k8s ReplicationController that helps managing scaling and pod lifecycle'}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2016-09-08 12:43:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
add a port number for the keystone-internal service to nova-api-create-cell

the nova-api-create-cell pod can't access the keystone-internal k8s service as the port number(5000) for the service doesn't exist in nova-api-create-cell's values.yaml,
so I add the port as a default

Change-Id: Ia5839955bfda4d8d743063d528ef28bf72cfe3a7
Closes-Bug: #1766753

commit_message:
Enable the multi-node deployment

 1) add a label for network node
   kubectl label node <node name> kolla_network=true

 2) rebuild OVS microservices for network and compute node
   For network node
   - neutron-openvswitch-agent-network
   - openvswitch-ovsdb-network
   - openvswitch-vswitchd-network

   For compute node
   - neutron-openvswitch-agent-compute
   - openvswitch-ovsdb-compute
   - openvswitch-vswitchd-compute

 3) deploy microservices into each node
   To network node
   - neutron-dhcp-agent
   - neutron-l3-agent-network
   - neutron-metadata-agent-network
   - neutron-openvswitch-agent-network
   - openvswitch-ovsdb-network
   - openvswitch-vswitchd-network

   To compute node
   - nova-compute
   - nova-libvirt
   - neutron-openvswitch-agent-compute
   - openvswitch-ovsdb-compute
   - openvswitch-vswitchd-compute

 4) remove br-ex from compute-node

 5) If “multi-node" option in cloud.yaml is false (= AIO
    deployment), OVS microserivces for compute node
    won’t be deployed to avoid duplicating deployment.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint multi-node-deployment
Closes-Bug: #1766831

Change-Id: I0c7a07ba0fef372f1e2762bcc41fdaff30a13609

commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: I6cb85818f107513a91a891eb8905f0a9a54dc716
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-05-28 12:07:47.000000000', 'message': "Retry journal recording in L3

Since journal recording can fail, and is not run in the same
transaction as router/FIP operations, it will lead to the resource
(router or FIP) to remain altered while a journmal record hasn't been
created.

L3 Flavors should solve this issue comprehensively, but we need a
solution until it's stable, which can also be backported to stable
branches. Hence, this fix should address 99% or the cases.

Change-Id: Ibef0db9a58d86a85ffd948a35db983863999d319
Closes-Bug: #1738246

commit_message:
Retry journal recording in L3

Since journal recording can fail, and is not run in the same
transaction as router/FIP operations, it will lead to the resource
(router or FIP) to remain altered while a journmal record hasn't been
created.

L3 Flavors should solve this issue comprehensively, but we need a
solution until it's stable, which can also be backported to stable
branches. Hence, this fix should address 99% or the cases.

Change-Id: Ibef0db9a58d86a85ffd948a35db983863999d319
Closes-Bug: #1738246

commit_message:
Default some flavor fields loaded from instance

For whatever reason, the non-notification Flavor object
does not provide defaults for disabled, is_public or swap
fields even though the data model does.

Any versioned notifications using the FlavorPayload are
pulling those from the embedded instance.flavor, which
could have been migrated years ago, and might be missing
some fields from the embedded flavor (like these default
ones).

This makes sure that when the Flavor object is deserialized
these fields are checked and if they are not defined then
they are defaulted according to the data model.

Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem.os@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I71cdf53cb1904af061216b9ed08b2ceed4aa46e4
Closes-Bug: #1739325

commit_message:
base framework for cyborg client.

Include osc and httpclient lib codes.
In order to avoid reinvent the wheel, most of libs leverage
other openstack projects.

Use this command to list accelerators:
  # openstack accelerator list

ref:
  1. osc plugin
  https://docs.openstack.org/python-openstackclient/latest/contributor/plugins.html#

Change-Id: I90e39267eca3e91ce30807e00525cf637211e29d

Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>
'}]
commit_message:
fix tox python3 overrides

We want to default to running all tox environments under python 3, so
set the basepython value in each environment.

We do not want to specify a minor version number, because we do not
want to have to update the file every time we upgrade python.

We do not want to set the override once in testenv, because that
breaks the more specific versions used in default environments like
py35 and py36.

Change-Id: If807d4aba6e1dac661f6a380f4309d4563510106
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

'}]
commit_message:
Stop showing passwords when bootstrap script is ran

Currently this causes bash to echo all lines parsed
and executed; which makes it not so nicely output the
bootstrapping password.

This is not something we should encourage and have show
up in peoples logs or other so stop doing that.

Change-Id: Iac963a5df393d0359b4c8f93b8756ca168f6f193

[{'created': '2018-03-24 00:08:02.000000000', 'message': "Only sync the local cell in superconductor mode

When nova-manage db sync runs on cell1 in superconductor
mode, the [api_database]/connection config option isn't
set in the config file on purpose so the cell can't
reach the API database.

As a result, the db sync on the cell config can't hit
the API DB to sync cell0, which is not something we need
here anyway, but it results in an error message.

This tells the cell config db sync to just run it on the
cell database and not try to sync cell0.

Change-Id: Iac092762decd6de9e90e264f2998d255e8e40d00
"}]
commit_message:
Only sync the local cell in superconductor mode

When nova-manage db sync runs on cell1 in superconductor
mode, the [api_database]/connection config option isn't
set in the config file on purpose so the cell can't
reach the API database.

As a result, the db sync on the cell config can't hit
the API DB to sync cell0, which is not something we need
here anyway, but it results in an error message.

This tells the cell config db sync to just run it on the
cell database and not try to sync cell0.

Change-Id: Iac092762decd6de9e90e264f2998d255e8e40d00

commit_message:
Set workers=$API_WORKERS in glance-registry.conf

We use $API_WORKERS to throttle the number of workers
in other services but were not doing it for g-reg for
some reason, which by default will run ncpu workers
up to a limit of 8.

Change-Id: Idc81ce05546e6d625c10e2229256eafbe7c057a5
Closes-Bug: #1774781

commit_message:
Add flavor_id argument to router tests.

As neutron/tests/unit/extensions/test_l3.py is used networking-odl for
functional tests, it ignores flavor data because flavor_id is not
included in hardcoded argument list.

Change-Id: I1826f50233dcf83f991e78d59ce1d3df2bc9013b
Closes-Bug: #1769751

commit_message:
Stop testing neutron-lbaas in gate jobs

neutron-lbaas has been deprecated since long. Let's remove the
service from gate jobs and skip the relevant tests.

(10 comments)

probably echoing what others have pointed out - i forgot to hit submit before I got on the train... 

Looks like a neat general purpose utility.

Do you have use-cases driving requirements that it work like this?  My first guess for read-only was some sort of origination tier of proxies - not so much that you have a use-case with a fixed content?  Can you give some more details?  

But I find the very specific subset of knobs curious?  You make the cluster read-only, except for some specific accounts you set via config - *or* you *just* disable some specific accounts via sysmeta.  Do you have some informed experience managing config settings and sysmeta for the rate limit middleware that tells you the config whitelist and the sysmeta blacklist are going to be the most useful?  Do you see in value in allowing blacklist via config, or whitelist via sysmeta like the ratelimit?'}, {'account_id': 1009, 'date': '2015-10-13 17:28:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1009, 'date': '2015-10-13 17:30:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I addressed some of the comments from the previous patch set.  I'm thinking about the rest.

And I probably need to add more tests."}, {'account_id': 1009, 'date': '2015-10-13 17:49:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-10-13 21:36:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Just from an organizational perspective I think it makes zero sense for the read_only middlware to get top tier billing.

If you cp all that good looking rst from that weird new file into a doc string in the middleware (right next to the code!!!) and then look at the middlewares.rst in doc/source you can see how to insert a neat little auto doc stanza that would be some freaking amazing I can't even.

commit_message:
Adds read_only middleware

This patch adds a read_only middleware to swift. It gives the ability
to make an entire cluster or individual accounts read only.
When a cluster or an account is in read only mode, requests that would
result in writes to the cluser are not allowed.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I7e0743aecd60b171bbcefcc8b6e1f3fd4cef2478
